ommission, to authorizeappropriations for that Act, and for other purposes, having consideredthe same, report favorably thereon with an amendment and recommend thatthe bill as amended do pass.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">The amendment is as follows:</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Strike out all after the enacting clause and insert in lieu thereofthe following:<CODE-213>1</CODE-213><CODE-213>0</CODE-213><CODE-213>1</CODE-213><CODE-213>0</CODE-213><CODE-213>1</CODE-213><CODE-213>0</CODE-213><CODE-213>1</CODE-213><CODE-213>0</CODE-213><CODE-213>1</CODE-213><CODE-213>0</CODE-213><CODE-213>1</CODE-213><CODE-213>0</CODE-213></ITAG><ITAG tagnum="72"><CODE-213>1</CODE-213>andCx.14; <CODE-213>5</CODE-213>H4<CODE-213>1</CODE-213> anddegrees;<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>SECTION 1. SHORT TITLE, REFERENCE.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="20"><CODE-213>1</CODE-213> <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>(a) </ITAG><T4>Short Title._</T4>This Act may be cited as the ``Consumer Product SafetyImprovement Act of 1988''.<ITAG tagnum="20"><CODE-213>1</CODE-213> <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>(b) </ITAG><T4>Reference._</T4>Except as otherwise specifically provided, wheneverin this Act an amendment or repeal is expressed in terms of an amendmentto, or repeal of, a section or other provision, the reference shall beconsidered to be made to a section or other provision of the Consumer ProductSafety Act.<ITAG tagnum="72"><CODE-213>1</CODE-213>andCx.14; <CODE-213>5</CODE-213>H4<CODE-213>1</CODE-213> anddegrees;<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>SEC. 2. FINDINGS.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="20"><CODE-213>1</CODE-213> <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>The Congress finds that_</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="22"><CODE-213>1</CODE-213> <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>(1) the current organizational structure of the ConsumerProduct Safety Commission is ineffective in protecting the public againstunreasonable risks of injury associated with consumer products,</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="22"><CODE-213>1</CODE-213> <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>(2) the current structure of the Commission has preventedit, through the democratic process of majority rule, from taking promptaction to protect consumers,</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="22"><CODE-213>1</CODE-213> <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>(3) the General Accounting Office has suggested considerationof a change in the structure of the Commission to an agency headed by asingle administrator,</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="22"><CODE-213>1</CODE-213> <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>(4) an independent regulatory commission which operatesin a truly collegial manner would help to ensure continuity in decisions,the exchange of ideas, and a mix of perspectives and would allow for betterreasoned and more independent decisions than an agency in the executivebranch headed by a single administrator,</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="22"><CODE-213>1</CODE-213> <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>(5) however, to ensure an effective and collegialConsumer Product Safety Commission the Commission must be reorganized,</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="22"><CODE-213>1</CODE-213> <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>(6) such a reorganization must include a change inthe functions, role, and manner of selection of the Chairman of the Commission,</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="22"><CODE-213>1</CODE-213> <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>(7) as a part of such reorganization of the Commissionthe Commission staff must be made responsible to the entire Commissionto ensure the free exchange of information and opinions necessary to thefunctioning of an independent Commission,</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="22"><CODE-213>1</CODE-213> <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>(8) such reorganization must include<CODE-213>5</CODE-213> a <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>change in the quorum requirement to ensure that theCommission can efficiently conduct its business,</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="22"><CODE-213>1</CODE-213> <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>(9) such reorganization must occur promptly to reducethe risk of injuries to consumers who are currently exposed to hazardsbecause of the failure of the Commission, under its current structure,to act promptly, and</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="22"><CODE-213>1</CODE-213> <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>(10) other changes, such as improvements in the regulatoryprocess and improvement in the regulation of specific products, are alsorequired to protect the public against unreasonable risks of injury associatedwith consumer products.<CODE-213>1</CODE-213></ITAG><CODE-213>0</CODE-213><ITAG tagnum="74"><CODE-213>1</CODE-213>andCx.14; <CODE-213>5</CODE-213>H1<CODE-213>1</CODE-213> anddegrees;<CODE-213>0</CODE-213></ITAG><T2>TITLE I_AMENDMENTS TO ACTS</T2><ITAG tagnum="72"><CODE-213>1</CODE-213>andCx.14; <CODE-213>5</CODE-213>H4<CODE-213>1</CODE-213> anddegrees;<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>SEC. 101. IMPROVEMENT OF REGULATORY PROCESS.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="20"><CODE-213>1</CODE-213> <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>(a) </ITAG><T4>Advance Notice._</T4>Section 9(a) (15 U.S.C. 2058) is amended by inserting``(1)'' after ``(a)'', by striking out ``paragraph (1)'' in paragraphs(3) and (6) and inserting in lieu thereof ``subparagraph (A)'', by redesignatingparagraphs (1) through (6) as subparagraphs (A) through (F), respectively,and by adding at the end the following:<ITAG tagnum="20"><CODE-213>1</CODE-213> <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>``(2) The Commission shall publish an advance noticeof proposed rulemaking under paragraph (1) to commence a proceeding forthe development of a consumer product safety rule if the Commission findsthat there may be an unreasonable risk of injury associated with a productand a consumer product safety rule would reduce such a risk. After theCommission publishes a notice under paragraph (1), the Commission shallwithin 180 days of the date of the publication of the notice_</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="22"><CODE-213>1</CODE-213> <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>``(A) publish a proposed consumer product safetyrule, or</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="22"><CODE-213>1</CODE-213> <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>``(B) terminate the proceeding commenced by the noticeif the Commission determines that a consumer product safety rule is notreasonably necessary to eliminate or reduce the risk of injury associatedwith the product or termination is in the public interest.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="20">The Commission may extend for not more than 90 days for good causethe 180-day period.''.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="20"><CODE-213>1</CODE-213> <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>(b) </ITAG><T4>Costs._</T4>The Consumer Product Safety Commission shall conduct astudy of the feasibility of requiring each manufacturer of a consumer productwhich is subject to a consumer product safety rule to pay to the Commissionan amount to defray the cost of the Commission in promulgating the rule.The Commission shall complete the study within 1 year of the date of theenactment of this Act and shall report the results of the study to theCongress.<ITAG tagnum="20"><CODE-213>1</CODE-213> <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>(c) </ITAG><T4>Types, Monitoring._</T4><ITAG tagnum="22"><CODE-213>1</CODE-213> <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>(1) Section 7(b) (15 U.S.C. 2056(b)) is amended byinserting ``(1)'' after ``(b)'' and by adding at the end the following:</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="20"><CODE-213>1</CODE-213> <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>``(2) The Commission may only rely upon voluntaryconsumer product safety standards under paragraph (1) which are in existenceand which have been issued after consideration of the views of interestedpersons, including consumers and organizations representing consumers.The Commission shall establish and maintain a plan to monitor compliancewith voluntary consumer products safety standards if the Commission hasrelied upo<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>n<CODE-213>0</CODE-213> the standards under paragraph (1), has participatedin the development of the standards, or has monitored the development ofthe standards.''.<CODE-213>1</CODE-213><CODE-213>0</CODE-213></ITAG><CODE-213>1</CODE-213><CODE-213>0</CODE-213><CODE-213>1</CODE-213><CODE-213>0</CODE-213><CODE-213>1</CODE-213><CODE-213>0</CODE-213><CODE-213>1</CODE-213><CODE-213>0</CODE-213><CODE-213>1</CODE-213><CODE-213>0</CODE-213><CODE-213>1</CODE-213><CODE-213>0</CODE-213><ITAG tagnum="22"><CODE-213>1</CODE-213> <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>(2) Section 9(b)(2) (15 U.S.C. 2058(b)) is amendedby adding at the end the following: ``The Commission shall establish andmaintain a plan to monitor compliance with the voluntary standard reliedupon by the Commission.''.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="22"><CODE-213>1</CODE-213> <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>(3) Section 3(g)(2) of the Federal Hazardous SubstancesAct (15 U.S.C. 1262(g)(2)) is amended by adding at the end the following:``The Commission shall establish and maintain a plan to monitor compliancewith the voluntary standard relied upon by the Commission.''.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="22"><CODE-213>1</CODE-213> <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>(4) Section 4(h)(2) of the Flammable Fabrics Act(15 U.S.C. 1193(h)(2)) is amended by adding at the end the following: ``TheCommission shall establish and maintain a plan to monitor compliance withthe voluntary standard relied upon by the Commission.''.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="72"><CODE-213>1</CODE-213>andCx.14; <CODE-213>5</CODE-213>H4<CODE-213>1</CODE-213> anddegrees;<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>SEC. 102. PETITION FOR CONSUMER PRODUCT SAFETY RULE.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="20"><CODE-213>1</CODE-213> <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>The Consumer Product Safety Act is amended by insertingafter section 9 the following:<CODE-213>1</CODE-213></ITAG><CODE-213>0</CODE-213><ITAG tagnum="89"><CODE-213>1</CODE-213>andCx.14; <CODE-213>5</CODE-213>H3<CODE-213>1</CODE-213> anddegrees;<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>``petition for consumer product safety rule</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="20"><CODE-213>1</CODE-213> <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>``</ITAG><T4>Sec</T4>. 10. (a) Any interested person, including a consumer or consumerorganization, may petition the Commission to commence a proceeding_<ITAG tagnum="22"><CODE-213>1</CODE-213> <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>``(1) for the issuance of a consumer product safetyrule for a consumer product, or</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="22"><CODE-213>1</CODE-213> <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>``(2) for the amendment of such a rule for the purposeof reducing the risk of injury associated with such product.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="20"><CODE-213>1</CODE-213> <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>``(b) Such petition shall be filed in the principaloffice of the Commission and shall set forth (1) facts which it is claimedestablish that a consumer product safety rule or an amendment thereof isnecessary, and (2) a brief description of the substance of the consumerproduct safety rule or amendment thereof which it is claimed should beissued by the Commission.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="20"><CODE-213>1</CODE-213> <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>``(c) The Commission may hold a public hearing ormay conduct such investigation or proceeding as it deems appropriate inorder to determine whether or not such petition should be granted.<CODE-213>1</CODE-213></ITAG><CODE-213>0</CODE-213><ITAG tagnum="20"><CODE-213>1</CODE-213> <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>``(d) Within 120 days after filing of a petitiondescribed in subsection (b), the Commission shall either grant or denythe petition. If the Commission grants such petition, it shall promptlycommence an appropriate proceeding under section 7. If the Commission deniessuch petition it shall publish in the Federal Register its reasons forsuch denial.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="20"><CODE-213>1</CODE-213> <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>``(e)(1) If the Commission denies a petition madeunder this section (or if it fails to grant or deny such petition withinthe 120-day period) the petitioner may commence a civil action in a districtcourt of the United States to compel the Commission to initiate a proceedingto take the action requested. Any such action shall be filed within 60days after the Commission's denial of the petition, or (if the Commissionfails to grant or deny the petition within 120 days after filing the petition)within 60 days after the expiration of the 120-day per<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>i<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>od.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="20"><CODE-213>1</CODE-213> <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>``(2) If the petitioner can demonstrate to the satisfactionof the court, by a preponderance of evidence in a de novo proceeding beforesuch court, that the consumer product presents an unreasonable risk ofinjury, and that the failure of the Commission to initiate a rulemakingproceeding under section 7 unreasonably exposes the petitioner or otherconsumers to a risk of injury presented by the consumer product, the courtshall order the Commission to initiate the action requested by the petitioner.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="20"><CODE-213>1</CODE-213> <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>``(3) In any action under this subsection, the districtcourt shall have no authority to compel the Commission to take any actionother than the initiation of a rulemaking proceeding in accordance withsection 7.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="20"><CODE-213>1</CODE-213> <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>``(4) In any action under this subsection the courtmay in the interest of justice award the costs of suit to a prevailingpetitioner, including reasonable attorney's fees and reasonable expertwitnesses' fees. Attorneys' fees may be awarded against the United States(or any agency or official of the United States) without regard to section2412 of title 28, United States Code, or any other provision of law. Forpurposes of this paragraph and sections 11(c), 23(a), and 24, a reasonableattorney's fee is a fee (A) which is based upon (i) the actual time expendedby an attorney in providing advice and other legal services in connectionwith representing a person in an action brought under this subsection,and (ii) such reasonable expenses as may be incurred by the attorney inthe provision of such services, and (B) which is computed at the rate prevailingfor the provision of similar services with respect to actions brought inthe court which is awarding such fee.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="20"><CODE-213>1</CODE-213> <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>``(f) The remedies under this section shall be inaddition to, and not in lieu of, other remedies provided by law.''.<CODE-213>1</CODE-213><CODE-213>0</CODE-213></ITAG><CODE-213>1</CODE-213><CODE-213>0</CODE-213><CODE-213>1</CODE-213><CODE-213