d</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="22"><CODE-213>1</CODE-213> <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>(3) include a time schedule for additional actionsby the Commission with respect to such product.<CODE-213>1</CODE-213></ITAG><CODE-213>0</CODE-213><ITAG tagnum="72"><CODE-213>1</CODE-213>andCx.14; <CODE-213>5</CODE-213>H4<CODE-213>1</CODE-213> anddegrees;<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>SEC. 210. RECLINING CHAIRS.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="20"><CODE-213>1</CODE-213> <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>(a) </ITAG><T4>Survey._</T4>The Consumer Product Safety Commission shall conduct asurvey, using statistically significant samples, of_<ITAG tagnum="22"><CODE-213>1</CODE-213> <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>(1) all reclining chairs being sold in the UnitedStates,</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="22"><CODE-213>1</CODE-213> <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>(2) the retail outlets for reclining chairs, and</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="22"><CODE-213>1</CODE-213> <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>(3) manufacturers of reclining chairs to determinetheir compliance with voluntary industry manufacturing guidelines designedto reduce the entrapment of children in such chairs.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="20"><CODE-213>1</CODE-213> <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>(b) </ITAG><T4>Report._</T4>Within 120 days of the date of the enactment of this Actthe Commission shall report to Congress the specific number of recliningchairs, retail outlets for such chairs, and manufacturers of such chairsincluded in the survey under subsection (a) and the number of such chairsand manufacturers which are not in compliance with voluntary industry manufacturingguidelines designed to reduce the entrapment of children in such chairs.<ITAG tagnum="20"><CODE-213>1</CODE-213> <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>(c) </ITAG><T4>Commission Action._</T4>If the Commission determines that there isa substantial lack of compliance with such industry guidelines, the Commissionshall initiate proceedings under the Consumer Product Safety Act to establisha safety standard for reclining chairs to prevent the entrapment of childrenin such chairs.<ITAG tagnum="74">Purpose and Summary</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">The Consumer Product Safety Commission (CPSC) was established by Congress``to protect the public against unreasonable risks of injury associatedwith consumer products.'' However, the Committee is greatly concerned withthe Commission's recent performance in protecting consumers.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">The reported bill, H.R. 3343, would restructure and r<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>e<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>authorize the CPSC. In particular, it would alterthe Commission's admini<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>s<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>trative structure, by making both the Chairman andthe staff more responsive to the Commission as a whole. The<CODE-213>5</CODE-213> <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>legislation would improve and speed up the regulatoryprocess. The legislation would also increase the role of the states andst<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>a<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>te enforcement officials, such as attorneys general,in ensuring product safety, so that if the CPSC is unwilling or unableto act, states can step in to protect consumers.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">The l<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>e<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>gislation also would require action on certain products,such as all-terrain vehicles (ATVs), disposal cigarette lighters, and lawndarts. In particular, the legislation would require ATV manufa<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>c<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>turers to offer refunds for three whee<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>l<CODE-213>0</CODE-213> ATVs.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="74">Background and Need for the Legislation</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="89">i. background on cpsc_its function and authority</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="77">A. Function and Structure</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">The CPSC was established by the Consumer Product <CODE-213>5</CODE-213>S<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>afety Act (CPSA), passed in 1972. The four primepurposes of the Safety Act are:</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="23"> ``(1) to protect the public against unreasonable risks of injuryassociated with consumer products; (2) to assist consumers in evaluatingthe comparative safety of consumer products; (3) to develop uniform safetystandards for consu<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>me<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>r products and to minimize conflicting state andlocal regulations; and (4) to promote research and investigation into thecauses and prevention of product-related deaths, illnesses, and injuries.''</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">The CPSC is an independent regulatory commission. The statute providesthat it is to have five members, appointed by the Presi<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>d<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>ent and confirmed by the Senate. The Chairman isappointed by the Pres<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>i<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>dent from among the members, subject to Senate confirmation.Currently, however, the appropriation for the CPSC only provides fundingfor three Commissioners. The current Chairman is Ter<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>r<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>ence Scanlon, a Democrat. The other two Commissionersare Carol Dawson and Anne Graham, both Republ<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>ica<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>ns.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="77">B. Laws Administered</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">The CPSC administers several statutes.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="87">1. <CODE-213>5</CODE-213>C<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>onsumer Product Safety Act</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">This is the basic act administered by the agency. It gives the CPSCauthority to set standards for products, to ban products where standardsare inad<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>e<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>quate, and to o<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>r<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>der recalls. (These powers a<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>r<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>e discussed in more detail below.)</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="87">2. Federal Hazardous Substances Act (FHSA)</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Formerly administered by the old Dep<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>a<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>rtment of Health, Education and Welfare (HEW), theadminist<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>r<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>ation of this Act was transferred to the CPSC whenit was formed. This Act gives the Commission the authority to regul<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>a<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>te hazardous substances, for example, toxi<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>c<CODE-213>0</CODE-213> or flammable ho<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>u<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>sehold chemicals. It also applies to hazardous toysand allows the CPSC to recall dangerous toys.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="87">3. Poison Prevention Packaging Act</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">This Act was also formerly administered by the old HEW and was transferredto the CPSC. It is the authority for the regulations requiring ``child-proof''drug containers.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="87">4. Flammable Fabrics Act</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">This Act was formerly administered by the old HEW, the Departmentof Commerce and the Federal Trade Commission and was transferred to theCPSC. It provides the CPSC authority to set flammability standards forfabrics.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="87">5. Refrigerator Safety Act</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">This Act requires that refrigerator doors must be able to be openedfrom the in<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>side<CODE-213>0</CODE-213> to minimize the risk of suffocation to childrenwho may be trapped inside.<CODE-213>5</CODE-213><CODE-213>0</CODE-213></ITAG><ITAG tagnum="77">C. Authority of the CPSC</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">The Consumer Product Safety Act gives the CPSC authority to take certainactions, including establishing product safety standards, banning products,and ordering recalls. These powers are described in more detail here.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="85">7<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>1. Promulgation of Consumer Product Safety Standard</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">The Commission, under Section 7 of the Act, may promulgate ConsumerProduct Safety Standards. These standards could eithe<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>r<CODE-213>0</CODE-213> establish performance (as opposed to design) requirementsor warning and instruction requirments. (Section 27 of the Act also givesthe Commission the authority to require the manufacturer to provide performanceand technical data to purchasers.) Any requirements established under Section7 must be ``reasonably necessary to prevent or reduce an unreasonable riskof injury'' associated with the product. Current standards deal with suchissues as matchbook requirements and safety standards for walk-behind powerlawn mowers.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">However, the CPSC must rely upon voluntary standards rather than promulgatea mandatory standard when compliance with the voluntary standard ``wouldeliminate or adequately reduce the risk of injury addressed and it is likelythat there will be substantial compliance'' with the voluntary standard.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">The Consumer Product Safety Act re<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>q<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>uires an extensive procedure for a safety standardrulemaking. The agency is required to first issue and advance notice ofproposed rulemaking, a step that is generally voluntary for other agencies,followed by a notice of proposed rulemaking, followed by a final rule.If a voluntary standard is submitted which meets the criteria above, theCommission is required to terminate the rulemaking and rely on the voluntarystandard. As part of the rulemaking, the age<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>n<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>cy must do a preliminary and final regulatory analysis,including a cost-benefit analysis, and provide opportunity for an oralhearing (which is optional for most agencies, which generally rely on justwritten submissions in rulemaking proceedings).</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="87">2. Banned Hazardous Products</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">The Commission may, under Section 8 of the Consumer Product SafetyAct, promulgate a rule banning a hazardous product if a product presentsan unreasonable risk of injury and ``no feasible consumer product safetystandard under this Act would adequately protect the public from the unreasonablerisk of injury associated with such product.''</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="87">3. Recall Authority</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">The Commission, under Section 15 of the Act, may order a recall ofa product if a failure to comply with a consumer product safety rule, ora product defect, creates a substantial risk of injury to the public. TheCommission may require the manufacturer or any distributor or retailerof the product to take one of three actions at the election of the manufactureror retailer. The options are to repair the product, replace the productwith a safe equivalent, or to refund the purchase price, less a reasonableallowance for use if the product has been used for more than a year. Whilethe manufacturer has the choice of remedy, the Commission can require submissionof a satisfactory action plan, which gives the agency influence over thechoice of remedy.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">The Act also requires manufacturers, distributors, and retailers toreport to the Commission information regarding likely product defects.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">As a practical matter, most recalls are agreed to by the agency andthe manufacturer, as opposed to ordered under the Act.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="87">4. Imminent Hazard Authority</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">As an alternative to a Section 15 recall, the Commission can filea Section 12 ``imminent hazard'' case in a U.S. District Court seekingthe seizure of a consumer product which ``presents imminent and unreasonablerisk of death, serious illness or severe personal injury.'' The court maygrant appropriate relief, including<CODE-213>5</CODE-213> <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>requiring a recall or approp<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>ria<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>te warning. The agency may take this action notwithstandingthe existence of a consumer product safety rule applicable to the productor the pendency of any administrative or judicial proceedings under anyother provision of the Act. </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="87">5. Regulation of Chronic Hazards  </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">The<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>r<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>e are special procedures that must be followed toregulate ``chronic'' hazards. The Commission may not begin the rulemakingprocess relating to chronic hazards (``a risk of cancer, bir<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>t<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>h defects, or gene mutations from a consumer product'')until the agency has first requested a Chronic Hazard Advisory Panel toreview the scientific data and other info<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>r<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>mation relating to the risk to determine ``if anysubstance in the product is a carcinogen, mutagen, or a teratogen'' andreports to the Commission. The agency must consider the report of the panelin its rulemaking. </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Each Chronic Hazard Advisory Panel must consist of severn membersappointed by the CPSC from a list of scientists submitted by the Presidentof the National Academy of Sciences. Panel members cannot be federal employeesand cannot receive compensation f<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>ro<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>m or have substantial financial interest in a<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>n<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>y manufacturer, distribut<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>o<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>r or retailer of a consumer product. </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="87"/><T3>6. Exclusions From Jurisdiction  </T3><ITAG tagnum="21">Certain products are excluded fr<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>o<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>m the Commission's jurisdiction. These include productsnot customarily produced or distributed for sale to or use or consumptionby consumers, tobacco and tobacco products, moto<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>r<CODE-213>0</CODE-213> vehicles, pesticides, firear<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>m<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>s, aircraft, boats, drugs or c<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>o<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>smetics, and food. The rationale for most of theseexclusions is that these products are regulated by ot<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>he<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>r agencies under other statutes (i.e., NHTSA, FAA,Coast Guard, FDA). </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">In addition, fixed site amusement parks (but not mobile amusementrides) are cur<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>r<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>ently excluded from the agency's jurisdiction.  </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="87"/><T3>7. Legislative Veto  </T3><ITAG tagnum="21">Most of the Acts administered by the agency have a legislative vetoprovision. These generally allow both Houses to veto any consu<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>me<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>r product safety rule within 90 calendar days (two-Houseveto) or one House to veto within 60 calendar days if <CODE-213>5</CODE-213>t<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>he other House does not object within 30 calendardays (one and a half House veto). </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="87">8. Preemption of State Action  </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">The Act preempts any different state or local standards which aredesigned to deal with the same risk of injury as a federal consumer prod<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>u<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>ct safety standard. This preemption does not preventthe federal government or state and local governments from establishingstricter safety standards applicable to products for their <T3>own </T3>use (i.e., as part of a government procurement of a product.<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>)<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>  </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">The Commission may waive preemption if a state or local safety standard``provides a significantly higher degree of protection'' than the federalstandard and it ``does not unduly burden interstate commerce.'' In consideringwhether there is an undue burden on interstate commerce, the agency isrequired to consider certain factors, such as the technological and economicfeasibility of comp<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>l<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>iance, the cost of compliance, the geographic distributionof the product, the probability of other states or local governments applyingfor a waiver and the need for a national, uniform standard for the produ<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>c<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>t.  </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="87"/><T3>9. Private Remedies  </T3><ITAG tagnum="21">Persons injured as a result of a knowing or willful violation of aCommission rule or order may sue in federal district court as long as theamount in controversy exceed<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>s<CODE-213>0</CODE-213> $10,000. Thus, violation of a Commission rule cangive rise to federal court jurisdiction in a product liability suit. </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Private parties may sue to comple enforcement of a consumer productsafety rule or a recall order, if the federal government has not takenenforcement action. The federal government must receive 30 days advancenotice of such a suit.  </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Compliance with Commission rules or order<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>s<CODE-213>0</CODE-213> under the CPSA does not relive any person from liabilityunder common law or state statutory law.  </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">The failure of the CPSC to take action with respect to the safetyof a consumer product is not admissible in evidence in litigation undercommon or state law rel<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>a<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>ting to such product. </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="85">7<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>10. Restrictions on Public Disclosure of Information</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">The Act includes restrictions on the CPSC's right to release informationto the public, restrictions which are more severe than those under theFreedom of Information Act. Before the agency can release to the public,either on its own or in response to a Freedom of Information Act request,information (whether it be staff studies or consu<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>m<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>er complaints) which will allow the public to identifya particular manufacturer, it must first notify the manufacturer 30 daysin advance and provide the manufacturer an opportunity to submit commentson the information. The agency must also take reasonable steps to assurethe accuracy of the information and that disclosure is fair and reasonablyrelated to effec<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>t<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>uating the purposes of the Act. In disclosing theinformation, the agency must, if requested by the manufactu<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>r<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>er, include the manufacturer's comments.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Before actually disclosing the information, however, the agency mustnotify the manufacturer 10 days ahead of time, during which time the manufacturermay seek a court injunction against disclosure, which can be granted ifthe CPSC has failed to follow the required procedures. (The 30 days and10 day notice<CODE-213>5</CODE-213> <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>periods can be reduced by the agency if it publishesnotice in the Federal Register that public health and safety requires alesser notice.)</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">These procedures do not apply in certain cases, for example, duri<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>n<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>g a rulemaking or adjudicatory proceeding or if theCommission has filed an action under Section 12, alleging that a productis imminently hazardous.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">In the case of information relating to the safety of a product orclass of products, whether or not such information would reveal the identi<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>t<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>y of a particular manufacturer, the agency must followprocedures to ensure that the info<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>rm<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>ation is accurate and not misleading.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">If the Commission mistakenly releases adverse information about aproduct, it must issue a retra<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>c<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>tion in an equivalent manner.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="87">11. Data Collection</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">One of the key functions of the agency is data collection on productdefects. The Commission receives information from consumer complaints,the National Electronic Injury Surveillance System (drawn from a sampleof hospital emergency room reports), and mortality data (based on deathcertificates and medical examiner reports).</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">The agency analyzes this data to try to identify new product hazards.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="89">II. Need For The Reported Legislation</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">The Consumer Product Safety Improvement Act of 1988 is a comprehensivelegislative proposal to overhaul and reorganize the Consumer Product SafetyCommission.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="77">A. The Problems<CODE-213>1</CODE-213></ITAG><CODE-213>0</CODE-213><CODE-213>1</CODE-213><ITAG tagnum="21"><CODE-213>0</CODE-213>The Committee's he<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>a<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>rings and investigations have revealed serious problemswith the CPSC and its current organization and leadership. The Committeehas particularly examined three case studies_all-terrain vehicles (ATVs),lawn darts and disposable lighters.<CODE-213>1</CODE-213></ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21"><CODE-213>0</CODE-213>The case of all-terrain vehicles is perhaps the mostinstructive example of the Commission's record under its current leadership.There are about 20 deaths and 7000 injuries a month related to all-terrainvehicles. Recent figures show that there have been over 1000 deaths and330,000 injuries since 1982. A more extensive discussio<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>n<CODE-213>0</CODE-213> of the ATV situation appears in III. below.<CODE-213>1</CODE-213></ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21"><CODE-213>0</CODE-213>The Subcommittee heard testimony from a father whose7 year old daughter was killed by a lawn dart. Current regulations requirelabeling of lawn darts and restrict sale to children. A CPSC survey lastsummer of 21 models of lawn darts found that all 21 failed to comply withthese regulations. A more recent survey of retailers (last winter) hasfound an almost fifty percent rate of violation at the retail level. Thus,the Commission has failed to ensure compliance with regulations alreadyon the books. <CODE-213>5</CODE-213>I<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>ndeed, partly because of the inability to enforcethese regulations, the Commission has recently proposed banning lawn dartscapable of causing puncture injury.<CODE-213>1</CODE-213></ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21"><CODE-213>0</CODE-213>About 170 people die annually from residential firesstarted by lighters, of which 120 are due to children playing with lighters.Ninety of the victims are children under five. In addition, recent testsshow that certain disposable lighters fail to comply with the industry'sown volunt<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>a<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>ry safety standard. Finally, in reaction to a long-pendingrulemaking petition from a nurse, the CPSC has approved an advance noticeof proposed rulemaking to address the child-resistance of lighters_thefirst step in a long regulatory process.<CODE-213>1</CODE-213></ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21"><CODE-213>0</CODE-213>The Committee has also examined the Commission'sadministrative structure and is concerned with the abuse of power by theagency's Chairman. In at least two separate cases, key personnel were transferredor detailed in retaliation for views which were consistent with the Commissionmajority, but i<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>n<CODE-213>0</CODE-213> disagreement with those of the Chairman<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>.<CODE-213>0</CODE-213> As discussed below, the two staff attorneys handlingthe ATV case were unilaterally removed by the Chairman in June of 1987.Similarly, the agency's Associate Executive Director for Compliance andAdministrative Litigation was arbitrarily and unilaterally detailed toanother position by the Chairman in August of 1987 and was temporarilyreplaced as the head of law enforcement at the agency by a non-lawyer.<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>H<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>e was restored to his position as director of compliancein October of 1987, after vigorous protest by the other two Commissionersand two days before a Subcommittee hearing. Such retaliatory actions againstFederal employees have no place in our system of government.<CODE-213>1</CODE-213></ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21"><CODE-213>0</CODE-213>The General Accounting Office pointed out, in anApril 1988 report to the Committee's Subcommittee on Commerce, ConsumerProtection, and Competitiveness, ``Consumer Product Safety Commission_PersonnelResources and Other Matters'' (GAO/HRD-88-57FS), that half of the Commission'sSenior Executive Se<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>r<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>vice employees were transferred at least once betweenJanuary 1, 1986 and October 30, 1987. During that same time period, 7 of29 professional staff members i<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>n<CODE-213>0</CODE-213> the CPSC's Compliance Directorate were transferredat least once. Four were transferred twice, and one employee was movedthree times. And even if these transfers and details were not made forinappropriate purposes, such frequent shuffling of personnel have a negativeeffect on an agency's ability to transact business and diminish the effectivenessof staff with a particular expertise.<CODE-213>1</CODE-213></ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21"><CODE-213>0</CODE-213>The Committee is also concerned with the inadequacyof the current level of product hazard reporting under Section 15(b) ofthe CPSA. Section 15(b) requires manufacturers (and distributors and retailers)to report to the CPSC instances where a product ``(1) fails to comply withan applicable consumer product safety rule; or (2) contains a defect whichcould create a substantial product hazard . . .'' A ``substantial producthazard'' in turn is defined as ``(1) a failure to comply with an applicableconsumer product safety rule which creates a substantial risk of injuryto the public, or (2) a product defect which (because of the pattern ofdefect, the number of defective products distributed in commerce, the severityof the risk, or otherwise) creates a substantial risk of injury to thepublic''.<CODE-213>1</CODE-213></ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21"><CODE-213>0</CODE-213>These criteria are somewhat subjective and industryoften prefers not to report potential hazards. Indeed, industry's failureto report is most pronounced for more severe hazards. According to a June6, 1988 letter from the CPSC to the Committee's Subcommittee on Commerce,Consumer Protection, and Competitiveness, during the period between October1982 and May 1988,<CODE-213>1</CODE-213></ITAG><ITAG tagnum="23"><CODE-213>0</CODE-213>the more severe the hazard presented by a product,the more likely it was that Commission Headquarters and Field Compliancestaff, and not industry, would initiate an investigation. For `A' level[the most severe] hazards, staff-initiated investigations outnumbered Section15(b) report-initiated investigations 18 to 2; for `B+' hazards, the marginnarrowed to 19 to 7. However, for `B' level hazards, Section 15(b) report-initiatedinvestigations outnumbered investigations initiated by staff.<CODE-213>1</CODE-213></ITAG><CODE-213>0</CODE-213><ITAG tagnum="21">Thus, as a recent CPSC memorandum, commenting on these statistics,put it, ``It is apparent that industry reports only the lower level hazardsand that the Commission staff has the task of uncovering the serious productsafety defects.''</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">The Committee is also concerned about the restrictions which Section6(b) of the CPSA impose on the Commission with respect to information disclosure.The 6(b) process is very resource intensive for the Commission. It is estimatedthat the Commission spends about half a million dollars and five employeeyears per year to implement the provisions of Section 6(b). At the sametime, the restrictions of Section 6(b) delay access by the public to informationdeveloped or received by the CPSC.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="77">B. The Proposed Solutions</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">To address these problems, this legislation would improve the Commission'sadministrative structure, its regulatory process, and the way it dealswith certain products. The legislation would also improve the state role,so that if the CPSC is unwilling or unable to act, states can step in toprotect consumers.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">The legislation would speed up and improve the regulatory processby requiring the Commission to begin the regulatory process if it findsthat there may be an unreasonable risk of injury associated with a productand that a safety rule would reduce the risk. This would not prevent thedevelopment of a potentially acceptable voluntary standard but rather shouldspeed up both the voluntary standard development process and the regulatoryprocess, for the benefit of consumers. And to examine a possible meansto reimburse the CPSC for the costs involved, the reported bill requiresthe CPSC to study the feasibility of requiring user fees to defray thecost of deve<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>l<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>oping a mandatory standard.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">The legislation also provides that the Commission may only rely onvoluntary standards which are actually in existence at the time the Commissionmakes its reliance decision and which are or have been developed througha consensus process, including consideration of the views of consumers.The Committee emphasizes that these changes are not intended to stop orhinder the development of voluntary standards in the future, but ratherto speed up and improve the process. Indeed, the requirement that the Commissionmay only rely on voluntary standards which are in existence at the timeof reliance is really just a clarification of existing law. For example,the Conference Report accompanying the 1981 amendments to the CPSA makesclear that the Commission can only defer to voluntary standards which areboth ``adopted'' and ``implemented''. Nevertheless, the Commission hassometimes mistakenly assumed that it should defer even beginning a rulemakingproceeding based on its hope that a voluntary standard might be developed.This clarification is intended to correct this misimpression.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">To address the problems raised by the lawn dart experience, the legislationrequires the CPSC to review its lawn dart regulations to determine if stricterrequirements, such as a ban, are required. (The Commission has alreadybegun this process, by proposing a ban of certain lawn darts.) The billalso provides that violation of a labeling requirement would give the Commissiongrounds for a recall. And to make it easier to take enforcement action,the bill establishes civil penalties under the Federal Hazardous SubstancesAct, similar to those under the Consumer Product Safety Act. Finally, toimprove the state role and speed up enforcement, the bill would allow stateattorneys general (or other state consumer enforcement officials) to seekimmediate court enforcement of safety rules if a violation results in imminenthazard or recurring or ongoing harm to the public, instead of having towait 30 days, as under current law.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">To address the ATV situation, the bill would require the ATV manufacturersto offer appropriate refunds to past purchasers of the dangerously unstablethree wheel ATVs. The bill would also ban the commercial sale of threewheel ATVs not subject to the ATV settlement agreement, extend free ridertraining to all past purchasers of four wheel ATVs, and require the CPSCto promulgate a safety performance and design standard for four wheel ATVs.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">To address the disposable lighter situation, the bill requires theCommission to begin proceedings to establish a safety standard for lighters,taking into account the need to protect children. (In response to a longpending petition and this legislation, the CPSC has recently issued anadvance notice of proposed rulemaking to address the child resistance oflighters.) The bill would also require the CPSC to adopt a plan to monitorcompliance with certain voluntary industry safety standards. And, in lightof the fact that the Commission took over two years to act on the petitionfiled by a nurse in 1985 to require that disposable lighters be child-resistant,the bill would require the CPSC to act within 120 days on citizen petitionsto begin a rulemaking proceeding.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">To improve product hazard reporting, the legislation would supplementthe current Section 15(b) reporting requirements by requiring reportingin two additional instances. First, reporting would be required of productrelated lawsuits involving death or serious injury. The Committee recognizesthat the mere filing of a pro<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>duct<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>-related lawsuit does not mean a defect exists, butthe Commission should be provided information about such lawsuits to determineif further investigation might be warranted. Such information could serveas an ``early warning system'' for the Commission. Second, industry wouldbe required to report instances of failures of products to comply withapplicable voluntary safety standards which the Commission has formallyrelied upon under Section 7(b) of the CPSA, in lieu of promulgating a mandatoryrule.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">To address the problems caused by the information disclosure restrictionsof Section 6(b), the legislation would expedite the release of non-tradesecret information which was not developed by the Commission (such as consumercomplaints), while maintaining the current right of manufacturers to reviewand comment on brand specific information before release.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">To improve and reorganize the CPSC's administrative structure andto ensure that the Chairman of the Commission works closely with the otherCommissioners, the legislation provides that the Chairman is to be electedby the other Commissioners. This change would be effective 30 days afterenactment to quickly begin the process of rebuilding the Commission andensuring collegial decision-making. At the same time, to address the problemof retaliatory transfers, the legislation would ensure that top staff officialsof the Commission would be more responsive to the Commission as a whole.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">To speed the work of the CPSC, the legislation also provides for aquorum of two Commissioners when there are only three sitting Commissioners.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="89">iii. all-terrain vehicles_why a legislative refund option is necessary</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="77"/><T3>A. Background</T3><ITAG tagnum="21">All-terrain vehicles (ATVs) are three and four wheeled motorized off-roadvehicles. As a result of their design_a high center of gravity, solid rearaxles, in some cases a lack of suspension, and, in some models, only threewheels_they have a tendency to become unstable and tip over. This has resultedin numerous injuries and deaths, especially to children and teenagers.Since 1982, over 1000 people have been killed and 330,000 injured on ATVs.There are about 20 deaths and 7000 injuries each month associated withATVs. Almost one half of the injuries and deaths involve children under16.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Some in the industry, which is composed mostly of four Japanese firms,Honda, Suzuki, Kawasaki, and Yamaha, and one American firm, Polaris, havemarketed ATVs to children as young as six. Models marketed to childrenare smaller. Polaris, which markets only to adults age 18 and over andmanufactured fewer than 2000 three wheel ATVs, discontinued three wheelATV sales about two years ago. The industry contends that injuries aremostly due to <CODE-213>5</CODE-213>ow<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>n<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>er<CODE-213>0</CODE-213> misuse, such as driving while intoxicated or failingto wear a helmet, not to vehicle design.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">In response to reports of numerous injuries and deaths associatedwith ATVs, the Consumer Product Safety Commission (CPSC) established anATV Task Force in April of 1985 to review the safety issues r<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>aised<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>. In add<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>i<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>tion, on May 31, 1985, the Commission published anadvance notice of proposed rulemaking, preliminarily determining ``thatthere may be unreasonable risk of injury associated with the use of all-terrainvehicles (ATV's) which may be sufficiently severe to require regulatoryaction by the Commission'' and discussing alternative ways to address therisks presented by ATVs.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">In July of 1<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>9<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>86, the House Committee on Government Operations,after a hearing by its Subcommittee on Commerce, Consumer, and MonetaryAffairs, issued an oversight report finding that three wheel ATVs presented``both an unreasonable and an imminent risk of death and serious injuryrequiring immediate enforcement action'' by the CPSC. The report recommendedthat three wheel ATVs should be recalled.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">The CPSC's ATV Task Force reported to the Commission on September30, 1986. The report included a number of findings regarding the natureof injuries and deaths resulting from ATV use, including a finding thattypically, children under 12 are unable to operate any size ATV safely.The report also included a number of recommendations for future Commissionaction.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">The CPSC responded in two ways. Publicly, in a December, 1986 meeting,it decided to work with the industry on the development of a voluntarystandard, even though the agency expressed unhappiness with the industry'sefforts to date. The Commission also decided to ask the industry to voluntarilycease marketing to children under twelve (a request which was subsequentlyrefused).</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Secondly, in a December 1986 enforcement meeting which was not opento the public, the Committee understands that the Commission agreed tofile an action in Federal court under section 12 of the Consumer ProductSafety Act (CPSA). It was to declare ATVs imminently hazardous and requirea notice, a warning, free training for all past and future purchasers,and require manufacturers to offer refunds, at the purchasers' option,for all adult sized ATVs purchased for children under 16 and all otherthree wheel ATVs. Under section 12 of the law, if the court finds thata product, namely ATVs, present an ``imminent and unreasonable risk ofdeath, serious illness or severe personal injury'', it can order appropriaterelief, including requiring a recall, refund or appropriate warning.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Throughout 1987, the Commission legal staff, working with the JusticeDepartment, prepared for the initiation of the enforcement action. However,the work of the agency was serious<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>ly<CODE-213>0</CODE-213> disrupted when the Chairman of the Commission, inearly June of 1987, unilaterally removed two experienced attorneys fromthe CPSC's ATV litigation team, over the vigorous protests of the othertwo Commissioners. While the replacement attorneys were experienced lawyers,they lacked the expertise in the ATV matter that the two original attorneyshad. Thus, the replacement of the attorneys caused delay.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">In November 1987, the Committee's Subcommittee on Commerce, ConsumerProtection<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>,<CODE-213>0</CODE-213> and Competitiveness approved, by an 11-4 bipartisanvote, this legislation to reauthorize the CPSC. As introduced, this legislationincluded a provision requiring ATV manufacturers to offer refunds or similarremedies to past purchasers of certain ATVs.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="77">B. The Complaint and Consent Decrees</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">In late November, the CPSC<CODE-213>5</CODE-213> <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>initiated settlement discussions with the ATV industry.The four Japanese companies negotiated together and the one American company,Polaris<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>,<CODE-213>0</CODE-213> negotiated separately. In mid-December, the CPSCdecided to seek consent decrees with the industry, and, at the urging ofthe Justice Department, decided not to inform the public and Congress ofits decision. The Commission was apparently willing to settle with theindustry without seeking the refund remedy, despite the Commission's earliervote and the Subcommittee's action. Under the Justice Department's plan,no information would be publicly released or provided to Congress untila December 30 press conference. However, the Committee's Subcommittee onCommerce, Consumer Protection, and Competitiveness, along with the Commerce,Consumer and Monetary Affairs Subcommittee of the Government OperationsCommittee, learned of the Commission and Justice Department plan and eachSubcommittee sent letters to the Commission on December 18, expressingconcerns at the reports and requesting information on the CPSC's activities.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">On December 30, the Justice Department and the CPSC filed a complaintagainst the ATV industry in U.S. District Court in Washington, D.C., alongwith two preliminary consent decrees, one negotiated with the four foreigncompanies and one negotiated with Polaris. The preliminary consent decreeswere binding agreements with the companies, but providing that certaindetails were to be subject to further negotiation. The Commission had earlierapproved the two consent decrees by a two to one vote.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">According to the allegations in the CPSC complaint:</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="23"> The risk of harm presented by ATVs is both imminent and unreasonable.Each time an ATV is operated, a rider who is not aware of the unique handlingcharacteristics of the vehicle . . . faces an unacceptably high risk that,at any moment and with no sign of impending danger, he or she will eitherbe killed or suffer a severe personal injury . . . defendants have falselyand deceptively promoted ATVs as safe, easy-to-operate vehicles for theentire family. . . . Defendants have created the illusion that ATVs caneasily and safely `go anywhere,' when in fact ATV operation on some typesof terrain is extremely hazardous.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">The preliminary consent decree required the ATV manufacturers to:</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="22"> stop marketing of three wheel ATVs;</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="22"> mail a notice to all known past purchasers of ATVs informing themof risks associated with the vehicles;</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="22"> provide all American distributors and ATV dealers with four-foot-by-four-footsigns containing the same warnings, which must be displayed prominently;</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="22"> offer to repurchase all new and never-before-sold three wheel ATVsin dealer inventories;</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="22"> affix warning labels to all ATVs marketed and sold in the UnitedStates;</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="22"> warn users of risks associated with ATVs in owner's manuals;</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="22"> establish a toll-free hotline phone number for consumer questionson ATVs and their risks and hazards;</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="22"> offer free hands-on training for all future ATV purchasers as wellas those who purchased ATVs in the past 12 months;</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="22"> agree not to oppose state legislation requiring licensing and certificationof ATV operators to the extent that legislation provides for age limitsfor ATV operators consistent with those in the preliminary consent decree;</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="22"> agree to undertake a public awareness campaign consisting of printadvertisements and radio and television commercials dealing with the potentialhazards and risks associated with ATVs; and</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="22"> agree to advertise minimum age limits for various ATV models (thedecrees require ATV manufacturers to market ATVs with engines between 70and 90cc only to those riders aged 12 and older, and to market machineswith engine size above 90cc only to riders aged 16 and older).</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">The preliminary consent decree also required the industry to attemptto reach agreement on voluntary standards satisfactory to the CPSC withinfour months of the Court's approval of the final consent decree. The CPSCwas required to provide the industry with a draft proposed standard bythe end of January. The draft proposed standard included requirments regardingcontrol and part design and vehicle performance, including lateral stability.The preliminary consent decree also provided that to the extent that threewheel ATVs met mandatory or negotiated voluntary ATV standards, they couldbe remarketed.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">The preliminary consent decree provided that a final consent decreewould be negotiated and submitted to the Court within 45 days (by February13). However, the CPSC, DOJ, and the industry subsequently agreed to, andthe Court approved, an extension until March 14, 1988.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">On Monday, March 14, the CPSC approved the final consent decree withthe ATV industry. The decree was filed in U.S. District Court on the sameday and was subject to the approval of the Court.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">The final decree was substantively very similar to the preliminarydecree filed on December 30. However, it included considerably more detailon the nature of the media awareness campaign and the warning and labelingthat the industry agreed to engage in.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">The final decree also provided more detail for the hands-on trainingprogram the industry agreed to. The industry also agreed to offer new ATVpurchasers an incentive (a U.S. savings bond worth $100 at maturity, fiftydollars in cash or a $50 merchandise certificate) to take a training course.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">On April 28, after an oral hearing on April 18, the District Courtapproved the final consent decree, with sli<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>g<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>ht modification, which included the ability of theCPSC to seek administrative relief under section 15 of the CPSA or Section15 of the FHSA, or both, including recall or repurchase, after December31, 1990.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">The settlement, however, provided no requirement for the ATV manufacturersto offer a refund or similar remedy to the estimated 1.5 million past purchasersof three wheel ATVs.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">It is important to note that of the two CPSC Commissioners who votedto approve the consent decree, Commissioner Carol Dawson expressed hercontinuing support of the refund remedy, noting that the ``refund provisionis not only fair, but would have sent a strong public safety message.''However, Commissioner Dawson stated her belief that it would be difficultand time-consuming to achieve the refund remedy in section 12 litigationby the CPSC. Chairman Scanlon continued to oppose any refunds for consumers.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">There are a number of other concerns with the consent decree. First,it is important to note that the manufacturers had already stopped productionof three wheel ATVs. Furthermore, while the consent decree required theindustry ``to attempt in good faith to reach agreement on voluntary standardssatisfactory to the Commission within four months of the Court's approval''of the final consent decree, there was no guarantee that such standardswould be developed within that time frame. Indeed, the four month periodexpired on August 28 and there is still no final agreement on voluntarystandards.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="77">C. H.R. 3991, the ATV User Safety and Equity Act and the CommitteeAmendment</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">On February 24, 1988, Congressman Barton introduced a companion bill,H.R. 3991, the ATV User Safety and Equity Act. That legislation would banthe sale of three wheel ATVs (except that individual sales by private individualswould not be prohibited) and would require manufacturers to offer refundsfor three wheel ATVs purchased before the date of enactment. It would alsorequire the CPSC to issue safety performance and design standards for ATVswithin one year. If the CPSC did not act within that time, the CPSC draftperformance standard of January 1988, would be mandated as an interim standard.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">On March 16, the Committee's Subcommittee on Commerce, Consumer Protection,and Competitiveness held a hearing on H.R. 3991. Testimony at the hearingconfirmed that a refund option would reduce serious injuries associatedwith ATVs. Indeed, an internal CPSC study submitted for <CODE-213>5</CODE-213>the<CODE-213>0</CODE-213> record projected that a refund option aimed justat three wheel ATVs could reduce serious injuries by 33,000 over four years.In addition, two of the three CPSC Commissioners, Commissioners Dawsonand Graham, indicated their support of refund legislation.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">The ATV industry argued at the hearing that ATV refund proposal wasunconstitutional. The industry argued that such legislation would be animpermissible interference with the consent decree, even though the legislationapplied generally to all manufacturers of ATVs and the consent decreesonly applied to five manufacturers. Indeed, Honda's attorney admitted tothe U.S. District Court that ``there are some other manufacturers.'' (Transcriptof Hearing of April 18 at pp. 43-44). The industry also argued that thelegislation would violate their equal protection and procedural due processrights, would constitute a taking of property without just compensationand would be an impermissible bill of attainder.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">The Committee's Subcommittee on Commerce, Consumer Protection, andCompetitiveness sought the advice of neutral legal experts at the AmericanLaw Division of the Congressional Research Service (CRS) for their viewson the constitutionality of ATV legis<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>lation. The op<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>i<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>nions by CRS indicating that the precedents supportthe cons<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>t<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>itutionality of such legis<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>lation follow:<CODE-213>5</CODE-213><CODE-213>0</CODE-213></ITAG><ITAG tagnum="51">Congressional Research Service,</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="52">The Library of Congress,</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="53">Washington, DC, June 6, 1988.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="55"/>To: House Committee on Energy and Commerce: Subcommittee onCommerce, Consumer Protection, and Competitiveness. Attention: RichardHumberman.<ITAG tagnum="55"/>From: American Law Division.<ITAG tagnum="55"/>Subject: Constitutional Challenges to Bill Banning Sale of Three-WheelAll Terrain Vehicles and Directing Refunds to Previous Purchasers.<ITAG tagnum="21">This memorandum is in response to your inquiry for a brief considerationof the constitutional objections which have been raised to H.R. 3991, 100thCongress, that would ban the sale of three-wheel all-terrain vehicles asa hazardous produc<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>t<CODE-213>0</CODE-213> under the Consumer Product Safety Act and that wouldrequire payment of refunds by the manufacturers to purchasers of such vehicleswho choose to return them. The bill is in response to a consent decreeagreed upon in <T3>United States </T3>v. <T3>American Honda Motor Co., </T3>CA No. 87-3525 (D.D.C.). A preliminaryconsent decree was approved and entered by the court on December 30, 1987,and a final consent decree is currently pending before the court. Underthe decree, all future sales of ATVs would be halted and a detailed programof training and education for ATV owners would be instituted. The ConsumerProduct Safety Commission would retain the right to seek further relief,including recall and repurchase, if new and substantial evidence indicatedthat a more extensive remedy was warranted.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Constitutional objections to the bill have been varied. First, itis argued that, by legislating to ban sales and to require recalls andrefunds, Congress is usurping the role of the courts in interpreting andapplying the CPSA and Congress is impermissibly interfering with the consentdecree. Second, it is argued that, by so legislating, Congress is deprivingthe manufacturers of the procedural due process protection they would enjoyif the CPSC were administratively acting under the statute. Third, it isargued that, by directing refunds to prior purchasers, Congress is impermissiblyinfringing upon a property interest of the manufacturers in violation eitherof substantive due process or the taking clause, both provisions of theFifth Amendment.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">While resolution of these issues is not completely free of doubt,it appears that the precedents, many of them cited and relied on by thememoranda submitted in opposition to the bill, support the validity ofthe action proposed to be taken.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="89">first</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">It is, of course, axiomatic that when Congress legislates on a broadrange of matters, the executive and judicial branches in appropriate circumstancesinterpret and apply the law. This state of things in no way deprives Congressof the power to legislate to expand, contract, or otherwise alter the law,even though issues of interpretation and application are currently beforethe courts. The rule goes back to the decision in <T3>United States</T3> v. <T3>Schooner Peggy,</T3> 1 Cr. (5 U.S.) 103 (1801), that a court must giveeffect to the law as it exists at the time it renders its decision, absenta manifest injustice arising from doing so, rather than applying the lawin effect at an earlier time. Thus, if a lower court decision, correctwhen rendered, has been disturbed by an intervening statute, the responsibilityof an appellate court is to set aside that judgment and apply the new law,absent very special circumstances. <T3>Id., </T3>110. See also <T3>Bradley</T3> v. <T3>Richmond School <CODE-213>5</CODE-213>B<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>oard,</T3> 416 U.S. 696, 711 (1974); <T3>Cort </T3>v.<T3> Ash,</T3> 422 U.S. 66, 74-77 (1975). Cf. <T3>Thorpe </T3>v.<T3> Durham Housing Auth.,</T3> 393 U.S. 268, 281-283 (1969) (applyingsame principle to agency regulations). Only if, for example, a change inthe law would deprive one of a right which had become vested by a courtdecision would the courts be precluded from applying the new law. See,e.g., <T3>Greene</T3> v.<T3> United States,</T3> 376 U.S. 149 (1964).</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Ordinarily, however, the fact that a court may have made an interpretationof law does not deprive Congress of the power to change the law, to ``reverse''a court decision in popular parlance, which does not, in fact, cons<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>t<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>itute an accurate statement of the jurisprudenceof the situation. Illustrative of this power is the old case of <T3>Pennsylvania </T3>v. <T3>Wheeling andamp; Belmont Bridge Co., </T3>13 How. (54 U.S.) 518 (1852);<T3>id., </T3>18 How. (59 U.S.) 421 (1855). <CODE-213>5</CODE-213>T<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>he Court ord<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>e<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>red a grant of an injunction requiring that a bridge,erected over the Ohio River under a charter from the State of Virginia,either be altered so as to admit of free navigation of the river or elsebe torn down. <CODE-213>5</CODE-213>T<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>he decision was based on the Court's reading of thecommerce clause and of a compact between Virginia and Kentucky. The injunctionwas promptly rendered inoperative by an act of Congress declaring the bridgeto be ``a lawful structure'' and requiring all vessels navigating the riverto be so regulated as not to interfere with it. Sustaining the new law,the Court opined: ``So far . . . as this bridge created an obstructionto the free navigation of the river, in view of the previous acts of Congress,they are to be regarded as modified by this subsequent legislation; and,although it still may be an obstruction in fact, [it] is not so in thecontemplation of law.'' <T3>Id., </T3>430.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">The <T3>Wheeling andamp; Belmont <CODE-213>5</CODE-213>B<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>ridge </T3>case has had a lengthy progeny in thecontext of Congre<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>ss<CODE-213>0</CODE-213> setting aside determinations by the Court that somestate action constituted an impermissible burden on interstate commerce.Because i<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>t <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>is Congress which is given the power to regulateinterstate commerce, it may authorize the States to do what the Court saysthey cannot. See, e.g., <T3>In re Rahrer, </T3>140 U.S. <CODE-213>5</CODE-213>545<CODE-213>0</CODE-213> (1891) (States authorized to discriminate againstinterstate traffi<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>c <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>in liq<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>u<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>or); <T3>Pr<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>ude<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>ntial Ins. Co. </T3>v. <T3>Benjamin, </T3>328 U.S. 408 (1946) (same as to insurance).</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">More pertinent are the many instances in which Congress has changeda statute to alter the interpretation a court, including the Supreme Court,has given to the law. See Henschen, ``Statutory Interpretations of theSupreme Court: Congressional Response,'' 11 Am. Pol. Q 441 (1983) (studingactivity over a period and reviewing earlier literature). For example,when in <T3>General Electric co. </T3>v. <T3>Gilbert, </T3>429 U.S. 125 (1976), the Court construed title VII'sban on sex discrimination as not reaching empl<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>o<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>yment practices based on pregn<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>a<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>ncy, <CODE-213>5</CODE-213>C<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>ongress responded with a statute which, while thelaw reached only part of the practices at issue in <T3>Gilbert, </T3>the Supreme Court construed as wholly overturning the<T3><CODE-213>5</CODE-213>G<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>ilbert </T3>approach to se<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>x<CODE-213>0</CODE-213> discrimination. <T3>Newport News Shipbuilding andamp; Dry Dock <CODE-213>5</CODE-213>C<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>o. </T3>v. <T3>EEOC, </T3>462 U.S. 669 (1983).</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Normally, Congress' enactment altering a court decision would applyonly prospectively, but there have been many instances in which personsentit<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>l<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>ed to receipt of some benefit as a result of a judicialdecision have been denied them. Perhaps the most famous example is thePortal-to-Portal Pay Act of 1947. After the Court had ruled that the FairLabor Standards Act required compensation for previously-uncompensatedpreliminary and incidental activities of employees in connection with theirwork, and claims amounting to at least $5 billion had been filed in federalcourts for time covered by the decisions, Congress enacted the law whichnot only prospectively denied payment for such time but retroactively cutoff payment for time already engaged in by employees. Although the SupremeCourt never passed on the validity of the Act, it was unanimously sustainedby all the courts of appeals to review it. E.<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>g<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>., <T3>Seese </T3>v. <T3>Bethlehem Steel Co., </T3>168 F. 2d 58 (4th Cir. 1948); <T3>Battaglia </T3>v. <T3>General Motors Corp. </T3>169 F. 2d 254 (2d Cir. 1948); <T3>Thomas </T3>v. <T3>Carnegie-Illinois Steel Corp., </T3>174 F.2d 711 (3d Cir. 1949). Thesame Act also created some employer defenses which were applied to casespending, some on appeal, to deny employees recoveries which they had wonbut which had not become final when the Act was passed. In one instance,after the Supreme <CODE-213>5</CODE-213>C<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>ourt had denied <T3>certiorari </T3>in the case, the Act was passed, and the Court on timelymotion modified its judgment of denial to authorize the district courtto consider the new defense. <T3>149 Madison Ave Corp. </T3>v. <T3>Asselta, </T3>331 U.S. 795 (1974); on remand, 79 F. Sup<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>p<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>. 4<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>1<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>3 (S.D.N.Y. 1948), 90 <CODE-213>5</CODE-213>F<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>. Supp<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>.<CODE-213>0</CODE-213> 442 (S.D.N.Y. 1950). A claimant has no vested rightin the decree of a court while it is subject to review and not final. <T3>American Steel Found<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>ries <CODE-213>0</CODE-213></T3>v. <T3>Tri-City Council, </T3>257 U.S. 184 (1921).</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">The fact of the existence of a consent decree in this case does notchange the analysis. A consent decree has ``attributes both of contractsand of judicial decrees.'' <T3>United States </T3>v.<T3> ITT Continental Banking Co., </T3>20 U.S. 223, 236n. 10 (1<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>9<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>75). Like a contract, it is an agreement bet<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>w<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>een the parties; the court cannot enter a decreeunless the parties <CODE-213>5</CODE-213>agree to every provision of it and it representsa settlement between the parties <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>that they consider acceptable and is not necessarilywhat they would have been entitled to under the law. <T3>United States </T3>v. <T3>Armour andamp; Co.,</T3> 402 U.S. 673, 681 (1971). On the other hand,the decree becomes a judgment <CODE-213>5</CODE-213>of the court that enters it, is <CODE-213>0</CODE-213><T3><CODE-213>5</CODE-213>res judicata, <CODE-213>0</CODE-213></T3><CODE-213>5</CODE-213>and is enforceable through <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>coercive authority. This attribute of the decreemeans that it must be and must remain within the boundaries of the lawunder which the parties have proceeded. Thus, in <T3><CODE-213>5</CODE-213>System Federation <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>N<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>o. 91, Ry. <CODE-213>0</CODE-213></T3><T3>Employees De<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>p<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>t. </T3>v. <T3>Wright,</T3> 364 U.S. 642 (1961), the Court ruled that a consent dec<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>r<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>ee must be modified, even over the object<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>i<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>ons of one or all the parties, when there has beena change in the applicable statute, inasmuch as a court's ``authority toadopt a consent decree comes only f<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>ro<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>m the statute which the decree is intended to enforce.''<T3>Id.</T3> 651. See  <T3>Firefighters Local Union </T3>v.<T3> Stotts,</T3> 467 U.S. 561, <CODE-213>5</CODE-213>576 <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>n. 9 (1984) (affirming principle). The decision in <T3>Local No. 93, Firefighters </T3>v.<T3> City of Cleveland,</T3>  478 U.S. 501 (1986), may be read as contraryto this proposition, but the opinion recites the principle stated above. </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Thus, the existence of a consent decree, especially one that has notyet been permanently approved, would seem not to stand in the way of legisla<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>ti<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>on. The parties obtain no immunity from future regulationby entering into such a dec<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>r<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>ee. Neither is such immunity conferred if the otherattribute of a consent decree, its contractual nature, is considered. Ithas long been settle<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>d<CODE-213>0</CODE-213> that government may not cont<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>r<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>act away its police powers. It must always retainthe power to act in the public interest even though it may have conferredsome interest, some right, upon private individuals. See  <T3>Stone </T3>v.<T3> Mississippi,</T3> 101 U.S. 814 (1880) (State may ban lotteries althoughit had earlier chartered the comapny to conduct a lottery);  <T3>Butcher's Union Co. </T3>v.<T3> Crescent City Co.,</T3> 111 U.S. 746 (1884);  <T3>Atla<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>n<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>tic Coast Line R. Co. </T3>v.<T3> City of Goldsboro,</T3> 232 U.S. 548, 5<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>5<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>8 (1914).  </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">The principal error of the line of argument that emphasizes interferencewith the courts would appear to be the attempt to draw an analogy withthe principle of  <T3>Hayburn's Case, </T3>2 Dall. (2 U.S.) 409 (1792).  See  <T3>Chicago andamp; S. Air Lines </T3>v.<T3> Waterman S. S. Corp.,</T3> 333 U.S. 103 (1948);  <T3>Connor </T3>v.<T3> Johnson,</T3> 402 U.S. 690 (1971). The rule in  <T3>Hayburn's <CODE-213>5</CODE-213>C<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>ase </T3>derives from the necessity that judgmentsof A<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>r<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>ticle III courts be ``final'' in order that thosecourts be vested with jurisdiction over a subject. The courts' decisionsmay not be su<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>bj<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>ect to revision or suspension by any other officer.As the citation of authority above of <T3>Schooner Peggy</T3> on to the present day establishes, this principleis in no way implicated by the power of Congress to change the law evenas to a matter under consideration by the courts.  </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">There is, to be sure, one important an<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>d<CODE-213>0</CODE-213> relevant case, which, in its language but not inits result, casts a shadow upon the argument here presented.  <T3>Un<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>it<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>ed States </T3>v.<T3> Klein</T3> 13 Wall. (80 U.S.) 128 (1872). <T3>Kl<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>e<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>in</T3> involved a statute couched in jurisdictionalterms that attempted to set aside both the effect of a presidential pardonand the judicial effectuation of such a pardon. The statute declared thatno pardon (for activities in<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>v<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>olving the Confederacy) was to be admissible in evidencein support of any claim against the United States in the Court of Claimsfor the return of confiscated property of Confe<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>de<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>rates nor, if already put in evidence in a pendingcase, should it be considered on behalf of the claimant by any court. Proofof loyalty was required to be made only according to provisions of certaincongressional enactments and when judgment had already been rendered onother proof of loyalty the Supreme Court on appeal was to have no jurisdictionand was to dismiss the case.   </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Clearly, the fault of the statute was that it infringed on the President'sconstitutional power to pardon and further it denied the courts the authorityto give effect to all the law, including constitutional law, relevant totheir decisions. The Supreme Court emphasized these problems, but it alsopremised its decision of the invalidity of the statu<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>t<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>e upon the fact that <CODE-213>5</CODE-213>it <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>``prescrib[ed] a rule of decision of a cause in aparticular way.'' <T3>Id.,</T3> 146. A<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>s<CODE-213>0</CODE-213> the cases already reviewed show, it cannot be afault of a statute that it prescribes a rule of decision of a cause ina particular way. With respect to rights created by Congress, as Klein'swas in part, Congress can prescribe rules of decision, by specifying standardsand burdens of proof, rights and entit<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>l<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>ements, and so on. It is such a st<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>atu<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>te that a court ordinarily applies. The fault, asalready noted, is that the statu<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>t<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>e pres<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>c<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>ribed a result that Congress could not substantivelyprovide<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>, a result contrary to the meaning a presidentialpardon has. The difficulty<CODE-213>0</CODE-213> is that the Court has, a<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>n<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>d recently, read <T3>Klein</T3> as standing for more than this, as standing for the propositionthat Congress had been attempting to prescribe a rule of decision on themerits. See <T3>United States </T3>v.<T3> Sioux Nation,</T3> 448 U.S. 371, 391-405 (1980), and <T3>id.,</T3> 424, 427-434 (Justice Rehnquist dissenting). It is possible,because of the factu<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>al <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>situation in both <T3>Klein</T3> and <T3>Sioux Nation,</T3> to take <CODE-213>5</CODE-213>this <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>reference as referring to the prescriptio<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>n<CODE-213>0</CODE-213> of a rule in a particular case, i.e., the ones beforethe courts at the time, and that <CODE-213>5</CODE-213>rule <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>was contrary to the law, but this may represent astrained reading of the two opinions. </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">In any event, whatever <T3>Klein </T3>may be read to mean, it is not readily applicable to theproposed bill. Congress would in enacting it be amending the CPSA specificallyto apply to the ATVs. The underlying law would be altered. The statutedoes not attempt to compel a court on the basis of a reading of the unchangedlaw to reach a different result. Congress compels a different result, assumingthe court on its own would have reached a different result, by statutorychange. The change in the law would necessitate a change in the consentdecree, because, just as in the <T3>System Federation</T3> case, a provision of the consent decree wascontrary to law.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">In other words, absent the existence of some ``vested'' right as aresult of a final court decision, the existence of a case pending in courtor the existence of a consent decree should have no bearing upon the powerof Congres<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>s<CODE-213>0</CODE-213> to enact legislation. </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="89">second</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">The due process procedural argument does not require lengt<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>h<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>y analysis. </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">When legislatures enact statutes which impose liabilities or providebenefits, they generally establish standards by which the entity re<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>s<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>ponsible for implementing the law determines whetherparticular individuals or groups of individuals must suffer the liabilityor rec<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>ei<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>ve the benefit. Obviously, in making such a determination,the agency must observe proper pro<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>c<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>edure which, at a minimum, is defined by the dueprocess clauses, but which may be further expanded by statute. A lengthylist of cases explores the meaning of due process in these contexts. E.g.,<T3>Brock</T3> v.<T3> Roadway Express,</T3> 107 S. Ct. 1740 (1987); <T3>Cleveland Board of Education </T3>v.<T3> Loudermill,</T3> 470 U.S. 532 (1985); <T3>Math<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>e<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>ws</T3> v.<CODE-213>5</CODE-213> <CODE-213>0</CODE-213><T3>Eldridge,</T3> 424 U.S. 319 (1976);<T3> Goldberg </T3>v.<T3> Kelly,</T3> 397 U.S. 254 (1970). T<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>he <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>CPSA itself requires the Board to follow an elaborateprocedure in determi<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>n<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>ing that some product is a hazard and must be withdrawnor other action must be taken.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">The opponent's argument is built upon an attempted extension of <T3>BiMetallic Co. </T3>v.<T3> Colorado, </T3>239 U.S. 441 (1915), and <T3>Londoner</T3> v. <T3>Denver,</T3> 210 U.S. 373 (1908), two cases that are seminal in thedevelopment of the administrative law conceptions involving the proceduredue when agency actions are either adjudicatory or legislative throughrulemaking. See53<CODE-213>0</CODE-213> United States v.<T3> Florida East Coast Railway Co.,</T3> 410 U.S. 224, 245 (1973). Accordingto the opponents' argument, the distinction between the one case, in whicha hearing on individual objections was required, and the other, in whichno hearing was necessary, was that <T3>Londoner</T3> invo<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>lv<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>ed a limited number of persons who were exceptionallyaffected by an assessment, whereas <T3>BiMetallic</T3> involved a valuation increase of all taxable propertywithin the jurisdiction. Since here there are only five manufacturer<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>s<CODE-213>0</CODE-213> concerned, a limited number up<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>on <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>whom there will be an exceptional effect, the argumentimplies, the manufact<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>u<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>rers must receive the <T3>Londoner</T3> result, procedural protection.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">More critical in distinguishing the two cases from the ATV situationis that both <T3>Londoner</T3> and <T3>BiMetallic</T3> concerned agency action pursuant to legislative delegation,even though in <T3>Londoner</T3> the assessment was finally imposed through legislati<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>ve <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>action of a body subordinate to the state legislature,whereas the ATV bill, if passed, would be purely a legislative action.The fact that the bill would affect known companies or individuals wouldbe irrelevant. The bill, if passed, would mandate a recall and refund.The only question would be whether any particular vehicle was in fact athree-wheeled ATV, a matter hardly meriting a procedural hearing. For example,when a state bans a lottery, that determines the matter; the lottery operatoris not entitled to some sort of procedural hearing, because there is nothingfurther to determine. Cf. <T3>Stone </T3>v. <T3>Mississippi,</T3> 101 U.S. 814 (1880). And the legislature may establishas a cause for revocation of a benefit or imposition of a detriment a plain,factual happening as to which the executing agency need only accord a <T3>pro forma</T3> kind of hearing. E.g., <T3>Dixon </T3>v. <T3>Love, </T3>431 U.S. 105 (1977) (revocation of driver's license uponconviction of offense implicates next to no procedure); <T3>Mackey </T3>v. <T3>Montrym,</T3> 443 U.S. 1 (1979) (same as to suspension of license forrefusal to take breath-analysis test). Certainy, an agency to divest someoneof a property interst has to give notice and an opportunity to be heard;but when a legislature enacts a provision which imposes a new conditionupon ownership with divestiture for failure to comply, it need not provideany notice at all, beyond publication of the law, to any affected party.<T3>Texaco </T3>v. <T3>Short,</T3> 454 U.S. 516 (1982).</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">In other words, after enactment of the law there would be no<CODE-213>5</CODE-213> <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>facts to adjudicate and thus no necessity for a hearing.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="89">third</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">It is also argued that by mandating a recall of already sold ATVsand requiring the manufacturers to give refunds to the purchasers, thebill would violate the Fifth Amendment, either the takings clause or thesubstantive aspects of the due process clause. The takings clause requiresjust compensation for the taking of property for a public use, and theCourt has analyzed regulation of the use of property as a form of taking,because of the deprivation suffered by the owner in not being able to makeprofitable use of the property. Substantive due process, once prevalentas a <CODE-213>5</CODE-213>limitation <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>upon government's ability to regulate economic interests,is a restriction upon governmental power to prescribe or proscribe certaineconomic activities. In the regulatory area, the Court has not drawn aclear line between the two concepts and sometimes has utilized both kindsof analyses in the same case. See <T3>Williamson County Regional Planning Comm. </T3>v. <T3>Hamilton Bank, </T3>473 U.S. 172 (1985) (1 and use plan restrictions).</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">The opponent's argument also stress<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>es<CODE-213>0</CODE-213> the retroactive nature of the refund obligation;necessarily, the requirement imposes a duty to undo a past occurrence_saleof ATVs_involving a financial detriment to the companies. It is evidentfrom the Court's precedents that retroactive economic regulation is subjectto scrutiny beyond the ordinary lenient due process review of such legislationin it<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>s<CODE-213>0</CODE-213> prospective operation, in that the retroactive effectof law must itself serve a valid purpose<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>.<CODE-213>0</CODE-213> <T3>PBGC </T3>v. <T3>Gray andamp; Co., </T3>467 U.S. 717, 730 (<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>1<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>984). Because, the opponents assert, government couldbar the <T3>use</T3> of ATVs in private hands, as well as bar future sales, andachieve its safety objectives, the imposition of the refund obligationdoes not serve a valid purpose.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">The retroactivity argument appears to be rebuttable through two interrelatedarguments which could prove convincing to Congress. First, Congress couldview the removal from private ownership of ATVs as a far-superior safetyprotection to a difficult-to-enforce ban on private use. Whether this stepis a superior one would appear to the kind of congressional judgement thatthe Court has said must be deferred to ``unless it is demonstrably arbitraryor irrational,'' <T3>Duke Power Co. </T3>v. <T3>Carolina Environmental Study Group, </T3>438 U.S. 59, 83-84 (1978).In the context of a state case, the Court has made the point that the reviewis so deferential that the challenging party may not offer evidence toprove that the legislature is wrong in its judgement that this purposewill be served, so long as the question is at least debatable, becausethe issue is whether the legislature ``could rationally have decided''that its goal would be effectua<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>ted<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>, <T3>Minnesota </T3>v. <T3>Clover Leaf Creamery Co., </T3>449 U.S. 456<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>, 466<CODE-213>0</CODE-213> (1981), though, of course, the challenging partymay present evidence to show that a judgment is wholly irrational. <T3>United States </T3>v. <T3>Carolene Products Co., </T3>304 U.S. 144, 153-154 (1938).</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Second, Congress could rationally determine that the refund obligationis a way of spreading the costs of furthering its safety purpose. <T3>Usery </T3>v. <T3>Turner-Elkhorn Mining Co., </T3>428 U.S. 1, 14-20 (1976). In this case,the Court sustained Congress' determination to impose upon coal mine operatorsthe liability of compensating <T3>former</T3> employees who had terminated work in the industry beforepassage of the law for black lung disabilities contracted in the courseof their work.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">With the retroactivity issue out of the way, it is possible now toreview the takings-substantive due process arguments. Although the caselaw is extensive in recent years, the most important general principleto observe is that the Court has found no substantive due process violationin the field of economic regu<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>lat<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>ion and the only takings violations it has foundhave involved actual deprivations of property or of the use of propertyfrom owners for the use and general benefit of the public. <T3>Nollan</T3> v. <T3>California Coastal Comm.,</T3> 107<CODE-213>5</CODE-213> <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>S. Ct. 3141 (1987) (in order to obtain permit toimprove house, owners had to dedicate strip of beachfront for public passage);<T3>Loretto</T3> v. <T3>Teleprompter Manhattan CATV Corp.,</T3> 458 U.S. 419 (1982) (buildingowner had to dedicate space on exterior of building at <T3>de minimus</T3> payment for installation of cable); <T3>Kaiser Aetna</T3> v. <T3>United States,</T3> 444 U.S. 164 (1979) (imposition of navigable servituderequiring public access to pond premised on owners' dredging at considerableexpense of channel that made it navigable). Otherwise, all the time acknowledgingthat some regulation could go too far, the Court has upheld land use andother regulation serving a public purpose which imposed considerable expenseupon property owners or which deprived them of much of the profitable useof their property. E.g., <T3>Penn Central Transp. Co.</T3> v. <T3>City of New York,</T3> 438 U.S. 104 (1978) (owner of building designateda landmark denied right to construct office building atop it from whichit reasonably anticipated a net of $2 million annually in rent); <T3>Andrus</T3> v. <T3>Allard,</T3> 444 U.S. 51 (1979) (ban on sale of artifacts made fromeagle feathers applied to existing inventory of dealer, leaving him onlythe profits to be earned in displaying artifacts); <T3>Keystone Bituminous Coal Assn.</T3> v. <T3>DeBenedictis,</T3> 107 S. Ct. 1232 (1978) (requirement that 50% ofcoal in support estate underlying certain structures be left in place toprevent subsidence damage, although companies in selling surface rightshad specifically reserved mining rights).</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Because the cases are numerous and present many complex factual situations,it may not be possible to draw general standards from the cases. It isnoteworthy, however, that the Court, and even some dissenters who wouldprefer closer scrutiny of regulation, place a high value upon the interestin the protection of health, safety, and welfare of the public. E.g., <T3>DeBenedictis, supra,</T3> 1242; <T3>Agins</T3> v. <T3>City of Tiburon,</T3> 447 U.S. 255, 260-261 (1980); <T3>Penn Central, supra,</T3> 144-150 (Justice Rehnquist dissenting). See<T3>Goldblatt</T3> v. <T3>Town of Hempstead,</T3> 369 U.S. 590 (1962) (terminating further miningwith severe consequent costs to owners of gravel and sand pit around whichtown had recently expanded); <T3>Hadacheck</T3> v. <T3>Sebastian,</T3> 239 U.S. 394 (1915) (restricting owner of brick factoryfrom continuing his use after residential growth surrounding factory madeuse noxious, reducing value by more than 90%). An important precedent is<T3>Miller</T3> v. <T3>Schoene,</T3> 276 U.S. 272 (1928), in which the Court sustained a governmentaldecision to require the destruction of ornamental red cedar trees infectedwith rust that threatened contamination of neighboring profitable appleorchards. The owner of the cedars was not entitled to compensation, held<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>the <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>Court, because the government could prefer the publicinterest in saving cash crops to the property interest in ornamental trees.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">It would thus appear that under the C<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>o<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>urt's precedents it would find rational and permissiblethe determination by Congress to require a recall of the ATVs and the impositionof the burden of protecting the public interest in safety upon the manufacturersrather than upon the private owners. The safety hazard is <CODE-213>5</CODE-213>n<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>ot alone a problem of the owners themselves but itas well presents a problem to third parties who may become involved inaccidents with the owners, who may use the vehicles themselves, or whomay without notice of the hazard purchase from an owner. In those circumstances,Congress could well decide, as it did in <T3>Usery</T3>, that the companies that had benefi<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>t<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>ed so much from the produce for years should bearthe costs of protecting public safety.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="89">fourth</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Recurring throughout the memoranda of the opponents of the bill isthe suggestion that because Congress would be legislating about a specificand particular subject matter, it would be acting improperly. It is indicatedthat by directing a ban on sales and a recall and refund of these ATVsproduced by five companies Congress is behaving like a court or the executiverather than like a legislature; in another place, the view is presentedthat something like a bill of attainder would be presented because thecompanies are so ea<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>s<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>ily identified, are, in fact, known beforehand.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Any argument that a legislature must act with such generality thatthose affected are not known in advance is not supported by any case law(save in those States which have constitutional provisions particularlydirected to the matter). To take one notable example, when former_PresidentNixon made arrangements for the custody and confidentiality of his papersand other materials produced during his time in office, Congress legislatedspecifically to provide rules applicable only to him. In <T3>Nixon</T3> v. <T3>Administrator of General Services,</T3> 433 U.S. 425 (1977), the Courtsustained that law against a variety of attacks, including bill of attainderchallenges, finding that Mr. Nixon constituted a ``legitimate class ofone.'' <T3>Id.</T3>, 472. To be sure, if a legislature's in<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>t<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>ent is to punish and does so directed to identifiablepersons, a law could be an impermissible bill of attainder or an <T3>ex post facto</T3> law. See <T3>United States</T3> v. <T3>Lovett,</T3> 328 U.S. 303 (1946). But the purposes of the bill in is<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>s<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>ue are regulatory rather than punitive. <T3>Nixon, supra,</T3> 468-484. That due process and equal protection arenot denied by legislation's limitation to an identifiable few, or evenone, is evident from <T3>City of New Orleans</T3> v. <T3>Dukes,</T3> 427 U.S. 297 297 (1976), in which the city council hadbanned all pushcart vendors from the French Quarter, save for those thathad been in<CODE-213>5</CODE-213> <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>continuous operation for more than eight years, anexception that benefi<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>t<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>ed one company and was apparently intended to benefitonly that company. The Court gave extreme defe<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>r<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>ence to the legislative classification and held thatonly if it were wholly arbitrary, in the sense of invidiously discriminatory,would <CODE-213>5</CODE-213>it <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>be struck down. In the course of the decision, theCourt overruled <T3>Morey</T3> v. <T3>Doud,</T3> 354 U.S. 457 (1957), one of the rare cases in recent yearsstriking down an economic classification. <T3>Morey</T3> concerned a regulation of ``currency exchanges'' which hadexempted by name the American Express Company from regulation. Thus, itappears that either by naming a company or individual or by so describingas to amount to the same thing, a legislature may enact an otherwise valideconomic regulation that applies to or exempts that company or individual.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Even if there were such a principle in constitutional law, outsidethe bill of attainder and perhaps some other contexts, it is difficultto see how the principle would be infringed by a law that reached all theindividuals or companies that are the source of the problem. Here, thereare only five manufactures of these kinds of ATVs. The law would applyequally to all of them. No singling out occurs.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">No singling out, that is, unless the opponents are su<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>g<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>gesting that Congress must legislate at an extremelyhigh level of generality. It could be that they are saying that Congressmust legislate about hazardous consumer products generally and must leaveto an agency the specific application of the general law. But, to reiterate,there is no such principle, as the <T3>Nixon</T3> case demonstrates, much less what may be drawn from <T3>Dukes.</T3></ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">The opponents do have one case on which to rely, but it is an idiosyncraticprecedent indeed. In <T3>News America Publishing</T3> v. <T3>FCC,</T3> No. 88-1037 (D.C. Cir., March 29, 1988), a divided courtheld unconstitutional a congressional provision denying the FCC the authorityto extend the time period of any current waiver of the prohibition of commonownership of a daily newspaper and a television station in certain marketareas. The only holder of waiver was the plaintiff company, and the courtheld the limitation to constitute a violation of the specialized equalprotection standard applied to First Amendment interests. E.g., <T3>Carey</T3> v. <T3>Brown,</T3> 447 U.S.<CODE-213>5</CODE-213> <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>455 (1980). Whatever the m<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>e<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>aning of this decision in the context in which itwas rendered_the area of press freedom_it is difficult to see qualifyingthe substantial amount of precedent reviewed above.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="89">conclusion</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">After reviewing the memoranda submitted in opposition to the billin question, we do not disc<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>ern<CODE-213>0</CODE-213> in the precedents cited nor in other precedentsstudied any substantial problem with the validity of the bill if enacted.It would not impermissibly interfere with the judicial process nor doesit subject any decision of a court to an impermissible revisory review.It does not deny the companies any procedural due process to which theyhave been held entitled. The case law with respect to substantive due processand takings, while not clear and settled, will admit of interpretationsthat would support congressional action. Finally, there would appear tobe no principle in the case law that would limit the specificity of thelegislation under consideration.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="56">Johnny H. Killian,</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="57"/><T3>Senior Specialist,</T3><ITAG tagnum="58">American Constitutional Law.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="51">Congressional Research Service,</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="52">The Library of Congress,</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="53">Washington, DC, June 21, 198<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>8<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="55"/>To: House Committee on Energy and Commerce: Subcommittee onCommerce, Consumer Protection, and Competitiveness. Attention: RichardHuberman.<ITAG tagnum="55"/>From: American Law Division.<ITAG tagnum="55"/>Subject: Constitutional Challenges to Bill Banning Sale of Three-WheelAll Terrain Vehicles and Directing Refunds to Previous Purchasers.<ITAG tagnum="21">In response to your inquiry, Johnny H. Killian, Senior Specialistin American Constitutional Law, by memorandum dated June 6, 1988 examinedthe relevant case law and concluded that legislation banning the sale of3 WD-ATVs and mandating refunds to purchasers who opted to return thempassed constitutional muster.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">As Mr. Killian is on leave you have asked us to review his memorandumin two particulars to ascertain whether his analysis hinges on the consentdecree in <T3>United States</T3> v. <T3>American Honda Motor Co.</T3>, as between being preliminary and permanent,and the absence of any ``vested'' right which might be interfered withby the previously described legislation. Your concern is prompted by thefollowing sentences at pages 6 and 9, respectively, of the mentioned June6 memorandum: ``Thus, the existence of a consent decree, <T3>especially one that has not yet been permanently approved,</T3> wouldnot stand in the way of [the] legislation''; ``In other words, absent theexistence of some <T3>`vested' right</T3> as a result of a final court decision, the existenceof a case pending in court or the existence of a consent decree shouldhave no bearing upon the power of Congress to enact legislation.'' (Emphasisadded.)</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Mr. Killian rightly notes at the outset that the resolution of theissues raised by the legislation is not completely free of doubt. Thisgeneral qualification is appropriate both because of the nature of C.R.S._weare not advocates_and the fact that as frequently happens, resolution ofissues is by way of decisions involving analogous situations, in this caseeffective displacement by legislation of court judgments.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">With these reservations as well as the overall qualification thatthere is in this as in many cases room for contrary argument, we are persuadedthat Mr. Killian's general conclusions do not turn on the status of theconsent decree, but clearly would be affected by the presence of some ``vestedright'' which would be cut off by the legislation under consideration.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">The noted sentence which appears at page 6 reflects the status ofthe decree at the time of the memorandum's preparation and exp<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>r<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>esses an <T3>a fortiori</T3> proposition, namely, by analogy with a final judgment,if Congress may by law supplant or deplace a permanent judgment, it goeswithout say<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>ing<CODE-213>0</CODE-213> that it may do so with respect to an interim ortemporary one.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">As indicated, Mr. Killian leaves no doubt that any interference bythe legislation with a ``vested'' right would affect the analysis. Sincea right of this nature is a property interest protected by the Due ProcessClause of the 5th Amendment against federal interference, a reservationalong these lines_one that appears frequently in the principal decisionsrelied on in Mr. Killian's analysis_is a virtual truism.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">In connection with the latter, the crucial question appears to usto be what ``vested'' right if any would be cut off by the legislation.Neither realization of a specific rate of return on an investment nor continuationof a speci<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>f<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>ic course of regulation fall into that category.``Federal regulation of future action based upon rights previously acquiredby the person regulated is not prohibited by the Constitution. So longas the Constitution authorizes the subsequently enacted legislation, thefact that its provisions limit or interfere with previously acquired rightsdoes not condemn it. Immunity from federal regulation is not gained throughforehanded contracts. W<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>e<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>re it otherwise the paramount powers of Congresscould be nullified by `prophetic discernment.' <T3>The rights acquired by judgments have no different standing</T3>.''<T3>Fleming</T3> v. <T3>Rhodes</T3>, 331 U.S. 100, 107 (1947). (Emphasis added.)</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">As previously explained, when advocates of one side or the other appearbefore your Committee on the mentioned legislation, question them on asserted``vested'' rights and how their situations differ materially and constitutionallyfrom those in the cases cited by Mr. Kill<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>i<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>an.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="56">Raymond J. Celada,</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="57"/><T3>Senior Specialist in</T3><ITAG tagnum="58">American Public Law.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">The Committee, in considering the CPSC legislation H.R. 3343, includedATV provisi<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>o<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>ns that are a modified form of H.R. 3991. The amendedbill clearly eliminates the concerns expressed by the industry about theconstitutionality of the legislation. It does not include a series of findings.It does not interfer<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>e<CODE-213>0</CODE-213> with the consent decree. Indeed, it supplementsthat consent order.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">The ban included in the reported bill applies to three wheel ATVsthat are not subject to the consent decree during its term. It requiresthat the CPSC give notice to all manufacturers of three wheel ATVs of theeffect of the ban in the legislation. That notice will presumably advisethe firms that are parties to the consent decree that the ban has no affecton those three wheel ATVs subject to the consent decree.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Most importantly, the legislation fills a void in the consent decree.It requires refunds by all three wheel ATV manufacturers to persons whopurchased these vehicles before the legislation is enacted, provided thatthose purchasers return those vehicles to the manufacturers. The bill directsthe CPSC to issue criteria by regulation governing refunds. The criteriawould require that manufacturers undertake a real and effective effortto notify the past purchasers or users of three wheel ATVs of the refundoption. The regulation will set forth a reasonable, fair and effectiveprocedure for return of the vehicles and the criteria for the refund. Thecriteria shall consider the age and condition of the vehicles and otherrelevant factors, such a depreciation. The intent is fairness and equitywithout windfalls to anyone and the Committee's interest in encouragingowners of these vehicles to return them for their own safety and that ofothers.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Refunds can be in cash or the equivalent in credit. Presumably, therefunds would be made by manufacturers through their dealers and that thedealers will be made whole as reasonable under the regulations and thelegislation. The dealers should bear no expense for this refund effort.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">The Committee expects the CPSC to maintain oversight over the implementationof the regulations to ensure fairness. If the regulations need revision,CPSC is not precluded from making those revisions.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">The bill deliberately does not provide a time limit on refunds. Thatis left up to the CPSC. We do not know that one is needed. The CPSC shouldconsider this issue consistent with the purpose of the legislation to providesafety. We think, however, that the CPSC should periodically review thestatus and effectiveness of the refund effort. The Committee expects theCPSC to keep us currently and fully informed about the development andpromulgation of the regulations and the actual refund program and otheractions regarding ATVs. Violations by the manufacturers are expected tobe punished by the CPSC.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">It is important to note that the bill also requires the CPSC to issuea rule stating that manufacturers of three wheel ATVs should not sell outsidethe United States any three wheel ATV returned to the manufacturer forpurposes of receiving a refund. They should be consigned to the scrap heap.The Committee does not want the manufacturers to visit these safety problemson people in other nations.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Other features of the legislation include an extension of the trainingprogram required by the consent decree without affecting the decree itselfand important information for prospective buyers of four wheel ATVs.<CODE-213>1</CODE-213><CODE-213>0</CODE-213><CODE-213>1</CODE-213></ITAG><ITAG tagnum="74"><CODE-213>0</CODE-213>Hearings<CODE-213>1</CODE-213></ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21"><CODE-213>0</CODE-213>The Committee's Subcommittee on Commerce, ConsumerProtection, and Competitiveness held one day of hearings on H.R. 3343,a bill to amend the Consumer Product Safety Act and related laws to improvethe performance of the Consumer Product Safety Commission, to authorizeappropriations for that Act, and for other purposes, and the related billH.R. 3443, a bill to establish an Administrator for Consumer Product Safetywithin the Department of Health and Human Services and to transfer thefunctions of the Consumer Product Safety Commission to the Secretary ofHealth and Human Services, and for other purposes, on October 27, 1987.Testimony was received from the Honorable Alfonse D'Amato, United StatesSenate; the Honorable George Miller, Member of Congress; the HonorableLarry E. Craig, Member of 