now,Riverside, California; the Honorable Terrence Scanlon, Chairman, ConsumerProduct Safety Commission (CPSC); the Honorable Carol Dawson, Vice Chairwoman,CPSC; the Honorable Anne Graham, Commissioner, CPSC; the Honorable NancyHarvey Steorts, Former Chairwoman, Consumer Product Safety Commission,President, Nancy Harvey Steorts and Associates; the Honorable R. DavidPittle, Former Commissioner, Consumer Product Safety Commission, TechnicalDirector, Consumers Union; the Honorable Barbara Hackman Franklin, FormerCommissioner, Consumer Product Safety Commission, Senior Fellow, WhartonSchool, President and Chief Executive Officer, Franklin Associates; MaryEllen Fise, Product Safety Director, Consumer Federation of America; JimRyan, American Association of Retired Persons; S. Anthony McCann, AssistantSecretary for Management and Budget, Department of Health and Human Services.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">The Committee's Subcommittee on Commerce, Consumer Protection, andCompetitiveness held one day of hearings on the role of the states in consumerprotection on July 23, 1987. Testimony was received from the HonorableWilliam L. Webster, Attorney General, State of Missouri; the HonorableMary Sue Terry<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>,<CODE-213>0</CODE-213> Attorney General, Commonwealth of Virginia; theHonorable Robert Abrams, Attorney General for the State of New York; theHonorable Hubert H. Humphrey III, Attorney General, State of Minnesota;the Honorable Robert T. Stephan, Attorney General, State of Kansas; BarryReid, Administrator, Governor's Office of Consumer Affairs, Atlanta, Georgia;Steven W. Hamm, Department of Consumer Affairs, Columbia, South Carolina;Mary Heslin, Commissioner, Department of Consumer Protection, Hartford,Connecticut; E. Edsel Moore, Director, Division of Radiation and ProductSafety, Department of Health Services, Cabinet for Human Resources, Frankfort,Kentucky. </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">The Committee's Subcommittee on Commerce, Consumer Protection, andCompetitiveness held one day of hearings on H.R. 2376, legislation to removethe special treatment accorded <CODE-213>5</CODE-213>tobacco <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>and tobacco products under the Consumer Product SafetyAct, on September 16, 1987. Testimony was received from the Honorable BobWhittaker, Member of Congress; the Honorable Charles Rose, Member of Congress;Larry King, The Larry King Show; Scott Ballin, Vice President, Public Affairs,American Heart Association, on behalf of The Coalition on Smoking or Health;Dr. Gregory Connolly, Director, Office for Non-Smoking and Health, MassachusettsDepartment of Public Health, Member, Expert Advisory Panel on Smoking andHealth, World Health Organization; Frederick Gahagan, Locust Valley, NewYork; Professor Richard Daynard, Northeastern University School of Law;the Honorable Charles O. Whitley, Counsel, Tobacco Institute; William Steele,Director, Tobacco Institute Testing Laboratory; the Honorable David Satterfield,Consultant, Tab<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>a<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>cco Institute. </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="74">Committee Consideration </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">On November 18, 1987, the Subcommittee on Commerce, Consumer Protection,and Competitiveness met in open session and ordered reported the bill H.R.3343, as amended, by an 11-4 roll call vote, a quorum being present. TheCommittee considered this legislation on July 12, August 3, August 4, andAugust 9. On August 9, 1988, the Committee met in open session and orderedreported the bill H.R. 3343 with amendment by a voice vote, a quorum beingpresent. </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="74">Committee Oversight Findings </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Pursuant to clause 2(l)(3)(A) of Rule XI of the Rules of the Houseof Representatives, the Committee's Subcommittee on Commerce, ConsumerProtection, and Competitiveness held oversight hearings and made findingsthat are reflected in the legislative report. </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="74">Committee on Government Operations</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Pursuant to clause 2(l)(3)(D) of rule XI of the Rules of the Houseof Representatives, the Committees notes that the Committee on GovernmentOperations has issued two recent reports related to the CPSC's responseto the hazards of three wheel ATVs, House Report 99-678 (July 16, 1986)and House Report 100-335 (October 2, 1987). Several of the recommendationsof that Committee are reflected in the ATV provisions of the reported legislation.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="74">Committee Cost Estimate</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">In compliance with clause 7(a) of rule XIII of the Rules of the Houseof Representatives, the Committee notes that this legislation would reauthorizethe CPSC at $39 million for fiscal year 1988 and $40 million for fiscalyear 1989.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="74">Congressional Budget Office Estimate<CODE-213>5</CODE-213></ITAG><CODE-213>0</CODE-213><ITAG tagnum="55">1<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>U.S. Congress,</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="52">Congressional<CODE-213>5</CODE-213> Budget Office,<CODE-213>0</CODE-213></ITAG><ITAG tagnum="53">Washington, DC, August 25, 1988.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="54">Hon. </ITAG><T4>John D. Dingell,</T4><ITAG tagnum="55">Chairman, Committee on Energy and Commerce, </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="55">House of Representatives, Washington, DC.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21"><T4>Dear Mr. Chairman: </T4>The Congressional Budget Office has preparedthe attached cost estimate for H.R. 3343, the Consumer Product Safety ImprovementAct of 1987, as ordered reported by the House Committee on Energy and Commerceon August 9, 1988. </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">If you wish further details on this estimate, we will be please<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>d <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>to provide them. </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="25">Sincerely,</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="56">C.G. Nuckols</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="57"/><CODE-213>5</CODE-213>(For <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>James L. Blum, <ITAG tagnum="58"/>Acting Director<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>).<CODE-213>0</CODE-213><ITAG tagnum="89">congressional budget office cost estimate</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">1. Bill number: H.R. 3343.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">2. Bill title: Consumer Product Safety Improvement Act of 1987. </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">3. Bill status: As ordered reported by the House Committee on Energyand Commerce on August 9, 1988.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">4. Bill purpose: To amend the Consumer Product Safety Act and relatedlaws to improve the performance of the Consumer Product Safety Commission,to authorize appropriations for that Act, and for other purposes. </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">5. Estimated cost to the Federal Government:</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="110"><C>7,tp0,i1,s10,6,6,6,6,6,6</C> <ITAG tagnum="96">[By fiscal years, in millions of dollars]</ITAG><H1> </H1><H1>1988</H1><H1>1989</H1><H1>1990</H1><H1>1991</H1><H1>1992</H1><H1>1993</H1><ITAG tagnum="1">Authorization level<D>6</D><D>40</D><D/><D/><D/><D/></ITAG><ITAG tagnum="1">Estimated outlays<D>0</D><D>40</D><D>6</D><D/><D/><D/></ITAG></ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">The cost of this bill fall within budget function 550.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Basis of estimate: H.R. 3343 would reauthorize the Consumer ProductSafety Commission for fiscal years 1988 and 1989. In fiscal year 1988,the bill would authorize additional funding over the 1988 appropriationlevel. Since Congress has already enacted appropriations for fiscal year1988 equalling $33 million, additional appropriations action would be necessaryfor 1988 funding to be increased for this program. The CBO assumes thatthe 1989 authorizations would be fully appropriated at th<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>e <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>beginning of the fiscal year. Outlays are estimatedusing spendout rates computed by CBO on the basis of recent program data.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">6. Estimated cost to State and local government: None.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">7. Estimate comparison: None.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">8. Previous CBO estimate: None. </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">9. Estimate prepared by: Lori Housman.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">10. Estimate approved by:<CODE-213>5</CODE-213></ITAG><ITAG tagnum="56"><CODE-213>0</CODE-213>C.G. Nuckols</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="57"/><CODE-213>5</CODE-213>(For <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>James L. Blum,<ITAG tagnum="58"/>Assistant Director for Budget Analysis<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>).<CODE-213>0</CODE-213><ITAG tagnum="21"> </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="74">Inflationary Impact Statement</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Pursuant to clause 2(l)(4) of rule XI of the Rules of the House ofRepresentatives, the Committee makes the following statement with regardto the inflationary impact of the reported bill.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">The legislation would improve the functioning of the CPSC. By improvingthe ability of the CPSC to protect consumers from unreasonable risks ofinjury associated with consumer products, the legislation should have ananti-inflationary effect.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="74">Section-by-Section Analysis</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="77">Section 1. Short Title, Reference</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Section one provides the short title, Consumer Product Safety ImprovementAct of 1988, and provides that, in general, references in the bill areto the Consumer Product Safety Act (CPSA).</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="77">Section 2. Findings</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Section two provides Congressional findings.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="89">title I_amendments to acts</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="77">Section 101_Improvement of Regulatory Process</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Subsection (a) amends section 9 of the CPSA to require the Commissionto publish an advance notice of proposed rulemaking for the developmentof a consumer product safety rule if the Commission determines there maybe an unreasonable risk of injury associated with a product and a consumerproduct safety rule would reduce the risk. The Commission would be requiredto publish a proposed rule, or terminate the proceeding (if the Commissiondetermnines that a rule is not reasonably necessary to eliminate or reducethe risk or if termination is in the public in<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>t<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>erest) within 180 days, although for good cause theCommission may extend this deadline by 90 days.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Subsection (b) requires the CPSC to conduct a study of the feasibilityof requiring each manufacturer of a consumer product subject to a safetyrule to pay to the Commission an amount to defray the cost of promulgatingthe rule. The Commission is required to complete the study and report theresults to Congress within one year.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Subsection (c) amends section 7(b) of the CPSA to provide that theCommission may only rely on voluntary consumer product safety standardsunder the CPSA if the voluntary standards are in existence at the timethe Commission decides to rely on a voluntary standard and have been (orare) issued after consideration of the views of interested persons, includingconsumers and consumer organizations. It also requires the Commission togenerally establish and maintain a plan to monitor compliance with voluntarystandards relied upon by the Commission under the CPSA, the Federal HazardousSubstances Act (FHSA) and the Flammable Fabrics Act.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="77">Section 102_Petition for Consumer Product Safety Rule</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Section 102 adds a new section 10 to the CPSA to provide an explicitprocedure for consumers to petition the Commission to begin a proceedingfor the issuance of a consumer product safety rule, or the amendment ofa rule to reduce the risk of injury associated with a product. The Commissionmust either grant or deny the petition within 120 days. If it grants thepetition, it must begin the appropriate rulemaking proceeding. If it deniesthe petition or fails to act within 120 days, the petitioner may begina civil action in a U.S. District Court to compel the Commission to initiatea rulemaking proceeding. The petitioner must demonstrate by a preponderanceof evidence in a de novo proceeding, that the consumer product presentsan unreasonable risk of injury and that the failure of the Commission toinitiate a rulemaking proceeding unreasonably exposes the petitioner orother consumers to a risk of injury presented by the consumer product.The new section 10 also gives the court discretion to award the costs ofsuit, including reasonble attorney's fees and reasonable expert witnessfees, to a prevailing petitioner.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="77">Section 103_Administrative Structure  </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Subsection (a) a<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>me<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>nds section 4 of the CPSA to provide that the Chairmanis to be selected by the members of the Commission. The term of officeof the Chairman shall be two years. To ensure that this reorganizationof the role and struc<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>tu<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>re of the Chairman's office and its relationshipwith the Commission is implemented quickly, the legislation provides thatthe term of the current Chairman as Chairman terminates 30 days after enactment,although the term as a Commissioner is unaffected. To ensure continuity,only Commissioners whose terms last at least two years are eligible tobe selected as Chairman.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Subsection (b) amends section 4(a) <CODE-213>5</CODE-213>of<CODE-213>0</CODE-213> the CPSA to provide that in maki<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>ng<CODE-213>0</CODE-213> appointments to the CPSC, the President shall considerindividuals with experience in the safety of consumer products or relatedfields.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Subsection (c) amends section 4(c) of the CPSA to provide that ifthe Commission consists of only three members, the quorum shall be two.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Consistent with the reorganization of the role of the Chairman, subsection(d) amends section 4(g)(1) of the CPSA to make clear that certain top staffof the Commission are officers of the Commission and serve, and are responsibleto, all Commissioners. The Director of Compliance is added to the listof officials for whom Commission approval is required for appointment.Subsection (d) also requires the Director of Compliance to be an attorneyand limits the appointment of individuals on an acting basis, to the positionslisted in section 4(g)(1), to 90 days. The subsection also provides thata majority of the Commission may vote to remove the officials listed insection 4(g)(1).</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Subsection (e) amends section 4(g)(2) to provide that subject to theavailability of appropriations, the Commission shall have a minimum personnelfloor of 525 full-time equivalents.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="77">Section 104_Information<CODE-213>5</CODE-213></ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Subsection (a) amends section 6(b)(4) of the CPSA to partially exemptfrom the requirements of section 6(b) information covered by the Freedomof Information Act which was not developed by the Commission and on whichthe Commission has included a disclaimer that the Commission is not responsiblefor the accuracy of the information. Under the amendment, the Commissionwould still be required to provide a manufacturer with an opportunity tocomment on brand-specific information before release and would be requiredto follow current law with respect to including the manufacturer's commentswith any release of the brand-specific information. The Committee wouldexpect such comments, if timely submitted, to be included, unless the Commissionis specifically requested otherwise by the manufacturer. However, the Commissionwould not be put in the resource-intensive position of assuring the accuracyof such information before its release.<CODE-213>0</CODE-213></ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Subsection (<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>b<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>) amends section 6(b)(<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>3<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>) of the CPSA to provide that before a United Statesdistrict court could enjoin the disclosure of non-trade secret information,it must determine that there will be no public benefit from such disclosure.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="77">Section<CODE-213>5</CODE-213> <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>105_Enforcem<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>ent<CODE-213>0</CODE-213> by State Attorneys General and Other Officials</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Section 105 amends the CPSA and the FHSA to allow a state attorneygeneral, or other state official with authority u<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>nd<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>er state law to enforce consumer product safety laws,to seek enforcement in U.S. district court for any violation of a consumerproduct safety rule, requirement of the FHSA relating to misbranded andbanned hazardous substances, or a recall order. As under current section24 of the CPSA, 30 days advance notice is generally required. However,the amendments provide that an action may be filed as early as practicableif the state official alleges that the harm to the public is ongoing, mayrecur, or presents an imminent hazard, and petitions the court for relief.The court may grant mandatory injunctions and other equitable relief andimpose a civil penalty as if the action were brought by the CPSC or theU.S. Attorney General.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Section 105 also amends sections 15 of the CPSA and the FHSA to allowstate enforcement officials to petition the Commission to recall a product.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="77">Section 106_Notification and Repair, Replacement or Refund </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Subsection (a) provides that a violation of <CODE-213>5</CODE-213>a <CODE-213>0</CODE-213>labeling requirement under the CPSA or the FHSA isdeterminative of the fact that the product presents a substantial producthazard and is subject to recall. Subsection (a) also requires the Commission,in its recall determinations, to consider the risks to the public but forbidscost-benefit analysis, which is inappropriate in an enforcement action.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Subsection (b) amends section 15(b) of the CPSA to require reportingof potential product hazards to the CPSA in two situations in additionto current law. First, reporting would be required of product-related lawsuitsinvolving death or serious injury. Second, reporting would be requiredof incidents of failures of products to comply with applicable voluntarysafety standards which the Commission has formally relied upon in accordancewith section 7(b) of the CPSA. </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="77">Section 107_Imminent Hazard Standard</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Subsections (a) and (b) amend section 12 of the CPSA to require theCommission and the court, respectively, to consider the risks to the publicin an ``imminent hazard'' action under section 12, but forbid cost-benefitanalysis, which is inappropriate in an enforcement action. </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="77">Section 108_Civil Penalties </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Section 108 amends section 5 of the FHSA by providing for civil penaltiesfor violations of the FHSA, similar to the civil penalty provisions underthe CPSA. </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="77">Section 109_Priorities </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Section 109 amends section 4 of the CPSA by requiring the CPSC toannually establish an agenda and priorities, after conducting a publiche<CODE-213>5</CODE-213>a<CODE-213>0</CODE-213>ring. </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="77">Section 110_Art Materials</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Section 110 of the legislation adds a new section 23 of the FHSA.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">New subsection (a) requires the CPSA to adopt the current voluntarystandard developed by the American Society for Testing and Materials (ASTM),(D-4236-86a), for chronic hazard labeling of art supplies, with changes,as a hazardous substance labeling standard under the FHSA. This placesresponsibility for enforcing the standard with the CPSC. </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">New subsection (b) makes the following changes in the current voluntarystandard: </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">(1) Changes the definition of ``art material'' to coincide with thestate laws that have been passed. This definition differs from the definitionin the standard in that it defines ``art materials'' as those that aremarketed as ``suitable'' for use by artists, instead of materials whichare ``intended'' for use by artists. </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">(2) Provides that the standard applies to precautionary labeling forusers of any age.  </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">(3) Provides that art materials producers shall submit to the Commissiontheir criteria for determining chronic hazards and a list of art materialsthat require hazard warning lables.  </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">(4) Provides that, at the request of the Commission, producers shallsubmit to the Commission their produce formulations and criteria for determiningchronic hazards.  </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">(5) Provides that chronic hazard labels include the name and addressof the producer, or repackager, and an appropriate phone number, alongwith a statement signfying that the art material is inappropriate for useby young children.  </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">(6) Provides that if an art material producer becomes aware of newinformation regarding chronic hazards in substances and products, thisinformation must be incorporated into labels within 12 months from thedate of discovery and that reformulated products must be labeled in accordancewith this standard.  </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">(7) Provides that the Commission may require full chronic hazard labelson art materials in containers smaller than one ounce if the Commissiondetermines that the product presents a chronic hazard despite its smallsize. If the information can not fit on the label, the art material shallhave a package insert which conveys all the labeling information required.(Under the ASTM standard, art materials in containers smaller than oneounce are not required to have full chronic hazard labels.)  </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">(8) Provides that the Commission shall take into account opinionsof various regulatory and scientific bodies when determining whether anart material has the potential for producing chronic adverse health effects. </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">New subsection (c) provides that if the Commission determines thata revision proposed by the American Society for Testing and Materials isin the public interest, it shall incorporate the revision into the standard.The Commission may amend the standard through regulatory proceedings, whichinclude an opportunity for oral presentation.  </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">New subsection (d) provides that within one year of the date of enactmentof this section, the Commission shall issue guidelines which specify criteriafor determining the chronic hazards of art materials, and shall periodicallyreview these guidelines to ensure they reflect changes in scientific knowledgeand in the formulations of art materials. In developing such guidelines,the Commission shall conduct a public hearing and provide reasonable opportunityfor the submission of comments.  </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">New subsection (e) requires the Commission to develop informationaland educational materials about art materials, and to distribute the materialsto interested persons. Interested persons include groups such as stateeducation departments, school boards and organizations of teachers.  </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">New subsection (f) allows the Commission to bring an action undersection 8 to enjoin the purchase of any art material required to be labeledunder the FHSA which is for use by young children.  </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="77"/><T3>Section 111_Authorization  </T3><ITAG tagnum="21">Section 111 amends section 32(a) of the CPSA to reauthorize the Commissionat $39 million for fiscal year 1988 and $40 million for fiscal year 1989. </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="77"/><T3>Section 112_Effective Date  </T3><ITAG tagnum="21">Section 112 provides that, in general, the effective date of the amendmentsmade by this title is the date of enactment.  </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="89"/><T4>title ii_related provisions  </T4><ITAG tagnum="77"/><T3>Section 201_All-Terrain Vehicles  </T3><ITAG tagnum="21">Subsection (a)(1) declares three wheel all terrrain vehicles whichare not subject to the ATV consent decree to be banned hazardous productsfor purposes of section 8 of the CPSA, for purposes of sales of such vehiclesby manufacturers, distributors or dealers. Thus, future commercial salesof such three wheel ATVs would be prohibited, but individual, private salesbetween consumers would not be affected. Three wheel ATVs which are notsubject to the consent decree include those whose sale or marketing isnot banned by the consent decree, such as used three wheel ATVs in dealers'inventory and all three wheel ATVs in existence after the expiration ofthe consent decree. futhermore, the sale of three wheel ATVs which aresubject to the consent decree would be a violation of section 19(a)(2)of the CPSA.  </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Subsection (a)(2) provides that the provisions in subsection (a)(1)would take effect 30 days after enactment. Before the expiration of that30 day period, the CPSC shall issue a notice to all manufacturers of threewheel ATVs explaining the effect of the provisions in (a)(1).     </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Subsection (b) requires manufacturers of three wheel ATVs to providepast purchasers who return their vehicles a refund determined in accordancewith regulations and criteria to be promulgated by the CPSC. The Committeeintends that the dealers not shoulder the financial burden of the returnand refund process. That cost will be borne by the manufacturers, not thedealers. Handling costs, paperwork, storage, time, the payment of refundsand other reasonable costs that may be entailed by the dealer would beconsidered as eligible costs that would also have to be paid by the manufacturers.The dealers' inventory of new and used ATVs would also be eligible forrefund just like any other consumer. </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">The subsection requires the CPSC to promulgate a rule, within oneyear, requiring the manufacturers of ATVs to notify purchasers of the availabilityof the refund, prescribing the procedure for the return of three wheelATVs for those who wish refunds, establishing criteria for determiningthe amount to be refunded, and stating that manufacturers should not selloutside the United States any three wheel ATV returned for a refund. Thecriteria established by the CPSC shall consider the age and condition andother relevant factors relating to the three wheel ATVs subject to therule and provide that the refund may, at the option of the purchaser, bein the form of a cash payment or in the form of credit against purchasesfrom the manufacturer.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">The subsection also specifies that a manufacturer of ATVs who failsto comply with the refund requirement shall be considered to have violatedsection 19(a) of the CPSA, relating to prohibited acts.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">The subsection requires that each three wheel ATV manufacturer reimburseits dealers for any expense incurred in connection with the refunds. Thesubsection specifies that the term ``manufacturer'' includes a distributor(generally the American subsidiary of a foreign ATV manufacturer whichactually distributes the ATVs to dealers).</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">The Committee expects the Commission, in prescribing the procedurefor the return of ATVs, to require the manufacturers to allow consumersto return ATVs to local ATV dealers for a refund. The Committee also notesthat the administrative regulations should be promulgated under noticeand comment procedures and would not be subject to the specific requirementsof section 9 of the CPSA.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Subsection (c) requires the CPSC to issue two consumer product safetyrules for four wheel all-terrain vehicles. The first rule would requirethe manufacturers and distributors of four wheel ATVs to extend the freetraining program, provided for in the consent decree with the CPSC, toall past purchasers. It also requires that purchasers be provided withstatistics on death and injuries to children under 16 for the prior fiveyear period. The second rule would require appropriate performance standardsand design characteristics for future four wheel ATVs.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">The subsection specifies the procedure to be followed in promulgatingthe two rules. The Commission is required to publish a notice of proposedrulemaking for the first rule within 45 days and a final rule within 180days. The Commission is required to publish a notice of proposed rulemakingfor the second rule within 120 days and a final rule within one year.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">The subsection also clarifies that compliance with a consumer productsafety rule promulgated under this subsection does not relieve any personfrom liability at common law or under state statutory law. This is consistentwith section 25(a) of the CPSA, which applies to consumer product safetyrules issued under the CPSA.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Subsection (d) provides that if after two years after enactment, lessthan one half of the States have enacted a law requiring the licensingof four wheel ATV operators, the safety training of such operators, theuse of helmets by such operators, and a minimum age of 16 for such drivers,then the CPSC shall conduct a study to determine what actions are requiredto impose such requirements or to otherwise protect children from the harmpresented by ATVs. Not later than two years after enactment, the Commissionshall provide an opportunity for public comment on its proposed report.Not later than 2\1/2\ years after enactment, the Commission shall reportthe results to Congress together with the comments received and its policyrecommendations.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Subsection (e) provides a definition of ATVs, based on the definitionin the consent decree.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="77">Section 202_Sleepwear</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Section 202 would require the CPSC to conduct a study under the FlammableFabrics Act to determine if a special flammability standard is needed forsleepwear other than children's sleepwear (for which a special standardalready exists). The CPSC must report the results of the study to Congressnot later than one year after the date of enactment. The commission shallspecifically consider the risks and benefits to the elderly.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">The Committee is aware that the Commission has already done work inthe area of elderly sleepwear flammability. The committee does not intendthis provision to result in a delay in ongoing work. Rather, the Committeeseeks to emphasize the importance of the CPSC's promptly completing workin this area.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">The Committee is also concerned about the Commission's enforcementof its existing children's sleepwear flammability regulations. The CPSChas promulgated a flammability standard applicable to children's sleepwearsizes 0 to 14, and has issued a set of definitions regarding what qualifiesas children's sleepwear. Evidence indicates that there has been a reductionin the number of children's death since the adoption of the children'ssleepwear standard.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">The standard adopted by the CPSC in practical terms means that garmentsmade of 100 percent cotton do not satisfy the standard. It appears thatsome manufacturers, primarily foreign manufacturers, have attempted toevade the standards by producing garments which are for all practical purposessleepwear but which vary in some small way from the standard. These productsare often made from cotton and displayed near complying sleepwear. Consumersthen purchase these garments and do not have the protection provided bythe flammability standard. In addition, since consumers may prefer thegarment made from cotton, these non-complying garments then have a competitiveadvantage over those products which comply with the standard. The CPSChas a policy statement that encourages retailers to segregate garmentsthat comply with the standard from those that do not comply, but that policystatement is often not followed. The Committee strongly urges the CPSCto investigate ways to ensure further adherence to that policy statement.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="77">Section 203_Lawn Darts</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Section 203 requires the CPSC to review its existing regulations andexemptions regarding lawn darts to determine if stricter requirements,specifically including a ban, are needed to protect consumers, especiallychildren. The Commission shall report its actions to Congress not laterthan one year after enactment. The Committee's concern is with lawn dartsthat have a potential to cause puncture wounds.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="77">Section 204_Lighters</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Section 204 requires that CPSC to begin regulatory proceedings toestablish a safety standard for cigarette lighters, specifically takinginto account the need to protect children. (In response to this legislation,and a petition to begin a rulemaking proceeding to require disposable lightersto be child-resistant that had been pending since 1985, the Commissionrecently issued an advance notice of proposed rulemaking on this issue.)</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="77">Section 205_Amusement Park Operators</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Section 205 would require the CPSC to conduct a study to determineif a minimum age should be established, under the CPSA, to promote safetyfor riders, for the operator of an amusement park ride. The Commissionshall report to Congress no later than 18 months after enactment.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="77">Section 206_Amusement Rides</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Section 206 amends the Consumer Product Safety Act to partially restorethe commission's jurisdiction over fixed site amusement rides.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Subsection (a) adds a new paragraph (15) to section 3(a) of the Actto define ``amusement ride.'' The term includes any device which carriesor conveys passengers over a fixed course within a defined area for purposesof amusing the passengers in the device. The device must be one that iscustomarily controlled or directed by a person who is employed for thepurpose of operating the ride and who is not a consumer with respect tothe device. An amusement ride which is not permanently fixed to a siteis a consumer product for all purposes of the Act. Such rides are typicallyfound in traveling circuses and carnivals. An amusement ride which is permanentlyfixed to a site is not a consumer product for purposes of section 7, 8,14, 15(b), 15(c), and 15(d) of the Act. Thus, the CPSC cannot promulgatesafety standards or bans regarding permanently fixed amusement rides. Thesubsection also adds a new paragraph (16) to section 3(a) of the Act todefine ``amusement ride operator.'' The term means the owner of an amusementride. The subsection also makes a number of technical and conforming changes.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Subsection (b) amends section 6(b) of the Act to make it applicableto public release of information from which the public can readily ascertainthe identity of the amusement ride operator.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Subsection (c) of the bill amends section 15 of the Act to add a newsubsection (h) to require any amusement ride operator who obtains informationwhich indicates that a serious injury occurred during operation of an amusementride the operator owns to inform the CPSC about the occurrence immediately.Serious injury is defined as trauma or other injury which actually resultsin death or a bone fracture or which requires overnight hospitalizationor which typically requires overnight hospitalization. The subsection alsoauthorizes the CPSC to order the amusement ride to cease operating untilit is repaired if the agency determines (after affording interested parties,including consumers and consumer organizations, opportunity for a hearingin accordance with section 15(f) of the Act) that an amusement ride thathas been involved in a serious injury, or is mechanically identical toa ride involved in a serious injury, presents a substantial product hazardand that corrective action is in the public interest.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Subsection (d) of the bill amends section 16(a) of the Act to providethat officers and employees duly designated by the CPSC may inspect, atreasonable times and in a reasonable manner, fixed site amusement ridesif the ride was involved in a serious injury or is mechanically identicalto a ride involved in a serious injury, including investigating the causeof the serious injury in which the ride was involved and to test the safetyof the ride. Such inspections must be commenced and completed with reasonablepromptness.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Subsection (e) requires the CPSC to issue regulations for the administrationof section 15, as amended by subsection (c) of this section. Such regulationsmust be promulgated within six months after the effective date.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Subsection (f) provides that the amendments made by this section willtake effect January 1, 1989.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="77">Secton 207_Indoor Air Pollutants</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Section 207 would require the CPSC to report to Congress on its activitiesto reduce exposure of individuals to various indoor air pollutants. Thereport would be due 90 days after the date of enactment. </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="77">Section 208_Labeling Requirement</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Section 208 would require the CPSC to issue a consumer product safetystandard for any toy for children which is manufactured after the dateof enactment, for sale in the United States, and which includes a smallpart (as defined in current or future CPSC regulations), to require thatthe packaging of such toy and any descriptive materials contain a cautionarylabel. The label shall state the age of children for which the toy is notintended and contain a description of the dangerous property of such toy.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="77">Section 209_Children's Products</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Section 209 would require the CPSC to report to Congress on certainproducts which pose a hazard to children. The report would be due 120 daysafter date of enactment. </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="77">Section 210_Reclining Chairs</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">Section 210 requires the CPSC to conduct a survey of reclining chairssold in the United States, retail outlets for such chairs, and manufacturersof such chairs, to determine compliance with voluntary industry manufacturingguidelines designed to reduce the entrapment of children in such chairs.</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">The CPSC is required to report the results of the survey to Congresswithin 120 days of enactment. If the Commission determines that there isa substantial lack of compliance with such industry guidelines, the Commissionshall initiate proceedings under the CPSC to establish safety standardsfor reclining chairs to prevent entrapment of children. </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="74">Changes in Existing Law Made by the Bill, as Reported</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21">In compliance with clause 3 of rule XIII of the Rules of the Houseof Representatives, changes in existing law made by the bill, as reported,are shown as follows (existing law proposed to be omitted is enclosed inblack brackets, new matter is printed in italic, existing law in whichno change is proposed is shown in roman): </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="74">Consumer Product Safety Act </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="65">* * * * * * *</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="89">definitions</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="21"><T4>Sec. </T4>3. (a) For purposes of this Act: </ITAG><ITAG tagnum="22"> (1) The term ``consumer product'' means any article, or componentpart thereof, product or distributed (i) for sale to a consumer for usein or around a permanent or temporary household or residence, a school,in recreation, or otherwise, or (ii) for the personal use, consumptionor enjoyment of a consumer in or around a permanent or temporary householdor residence, a school, in recreation, or otherwise; but such term doesnot include_</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="24"> (A) * * *</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="65">* * * * * * *</ITAG><ITAG tagnum="24"> (I) foodandCx.19;. The term ``food'', as used in this subparagraphmeans all ``food''andCx.20;, as defined in section 201(f) of the FederalFood, Drug, and Cosmetic Act, including poultry and poultry products (asdefined in sections 4 (e) and (f) of the Pou